const SEARCH_INDEX = {"1.Problems with broken tiles on the roof.pdf": "afrystar / assessment of double roman tile breakage (291121) the breakage of the tile, as you have indicated to me in the wasap has not happened in the depalleting nor in the packing, because the breakage is produced by a different type of stresses or tensions that the concrete tile suffers, in the transit of people on the roof tiles, they are different. although there is some breakage of the tile in the corners, according to the photos provided, most of them are longitudinal breaks in the centre of the tile. i am going to explain what i consider to be \"the problem of these roof tiles\" on a working hypothesis, which can be confirmed later with the data that can be taken from the roof tile. as a reference i take the photo you sent me of the 2 roof tiles during the manufacturing of the concrete tiles, there is a wear of the small slipper, small rollers, big slippers and big rollers, which gradually change the upper profile of the tile, causing an increase in the thickness and weight of the concrete tile. i believe that the measurements of the entire body of the tile must be very strictly controlled. as is normal, there is first a rapid wear of the interlock with the roller and the small slipper, and then in the body of the tile by the big slipper and big roller. a) a) when the thicknesses of the interlock areas are greater than the permitted tolerance, we can have a problem of coupling between tiles. causing a bad coupling try to get a good coupling, and there should always be a certain amount of play in the interlock, such as when the roller and small slipper are new. the problem with this bad coupling between the tiles, is that they can lift the tile on one side of the tile (the tile is suspended in the air), not being able to support the tile on the \"4\" front / rear ribs and with the transit of people on the roof tiles, when stepping on the tiles, the corners or the tile break longitudinally. in the case of the photos of the roof tiles, i consider that the tiles mounted on the roof are not supporting the \"4\" front / rear ribs of the tile. as there is an unsupported gap, the tile does not rest on the \"4\" front / rear ribs, and when the tile is stepped on, it breaks longitudinally. b) the upper part of the roof tile can also suffer from excessive wear in the big slipper, such as curved areas, these areas can cause bad support between the roof tiles and cause longitudinal breakage. in these curved areas there must always be sufficient clearance, so that there is always support for \"4\" front / rear ribs of the tile and does not allow one tile to swing over the other. arganda del rey 291121", "10.French tile quality extrusion.pdf": "notas sobre grabación de haji 120821. sobre la grabación en la producción de la teja french, lo primero que debemos conocer la granulometría utilizada y la humedad del hormigón. como complemento necesitamos conocer la información que utilizan para los ajustes de referencia de la maquina como pesos, espesores, inclinación, espacio entre rodillos y zapatas, para no hacer suposiciones incorrectas. en esta primera foto , se identifican todas las mejoras que necesita en la conformación de la teja, planos superiores de la teja y el ensamble. me gustaría ver una foto sobre el acabado de la teja/molde en los 2 laterales de la teja. en esta segunda foto se acentua la falta de conformación del nervio central de la teja y las ecamaciones de las 2 parte superiores de la teja, lo demás era pasable, estas variaciones por una parte esta el hormigón si está seco o humedo.(habría que verificarlo en cada caso) en esta tercera foto en relación a la anterior se acentua la falta de conformación de la parte exterior del ensamble y la menor incidencia de las ecamaciones de las 2 parte superiores de la teja,estas variaciones por una parte esta el hormigón si está seco o humedo.(habría que verificarlo en cada caso) en esta cuarta foto se acentua la falta de conformación del nervio central de la teja y las ecamaciones de las 2 parte superiores de la teja, lo demás era pasable, estas variaciones por una parte esta el hormigón si está seco o humedo.(habría que verificarlo en cada caso) en esta quinta foto quiero resaltar los grumos compactos que vienen en el hormigón, si se extrusionan a lo mejor no se anclan con el resto del hormigón.(habría que verificar si se producen en la amasadora o por la mezcla de las materias primas) muy importante la arena siempre sin ningún componente de “arcilla” y bien lavada. en esta sexta foto quiero indicar que hay que renovar, mover la columna de hormigón hacia delante con una pletina desde arriba, para que no forme una columna permanente que pueda crea una falta de alimentación al rodillo y la zapata. además que es conveniente mantener siempre, una columna de hormigón constante en la zona de alimentación al molde para dar una continuidad y evitar variaciones en la alimentación al rodillo y zapata en esta septima foto quiero indicar que es bueno y seguro,mantener la rejilla superior de la tolva ,para evitar introducir las manos y los brazos en la tolva de la extrusora. en esta octava foto al igual que en la cuarta foto, se acentua la falta de conformación del nervio central de la teja y las ecamaciones de las 2 parte superiores de la teja,por una parte esta el hormigón si está seco o humedo.(habría que verificarlo en cada caso) también cabe resañar señalado en el recuadro azul, los restos de hormigón generado en la parte lateral del molde en la parte del ensamble, habría que identificar como se genera despues del disco del rodillo y el lateral de la bancada. en esta novena foto cabe indicar la escamación superior central de la teja y la continuidad en la conformación del ensamble. en esta decima foto, quiero indicar que considero apropiado realizar la línea del corte en la parte trasera del molde, para evitar contactar en el empuje con la molde en la colocación de las tejas en la estanterías. la práctica siempre determina la mejor manera. arganda del rey 130821", "12.Reasons of tiles profile changes.pdf": "en respuesta a tú consulta he preparado esta nota: las razones de los cambios por desgaste en el conjunto de repuestos, son bastante claras, pero hay que separarlos por grupos, por lo que genera o provoca cada uno : a) rodillos grandes/pequeños, zapatas grandes y pequeñas, b) discos laterales, guías laterales. c) guías de la bancada de la extrusora o cadena empuje. d) cuchillas corte a) rodillos grandes/pequeños, zapatas grandes y pequeñas. un desgaste en cualquier de las piezas mencionadas, causa un “cambio de la medida del perfil inicial en la teja” todas las tejas tienen por diseño unas medidas en todas las zonas para obtener una resistencia a la flexión, un peso previsto, unas tolerancias entre las tejas en el montaje, unos espesores en las diferentes zonas de apoyo de unas tejas, unos espesores para los ensambles, etc. por eso la justificación de la utilización de los equipos de widia/tungsteno, es que estos cambios de medida tardan mucho en aparecer. siempre los primeros problemas de desgaste, son en la zapata pequeña, va cambiando de medidas sobre el perfil inicial, cambiando su acomodación, aumentando espesor hasta que pierde su perfil/acoplamiento y aunque desplace la zapata pequeña hacia abajo es imposible que haga su función, puede llegar hasta quedar la teja colgada y provocar roturas longitudinales en el tejado. por eso se cambia la zapata pequeña. (es necesario medir diariamente los espesores de los ensambles de la teja y los desgastes de la zapata pequeña, esto permitirá identificar cual es el punto crítico del desgaste) siguen por el rodillo pequeño, mientras que la 2ª zapata pequeña pueda funcionar conformando el ensamble, el rodillo pequeño con se cambia, pero cada vez más si pierde diámetro el rodillo pequeño por el desgaste, cada vez tiene que trabajar más la zapata pequeña para conformar el ensamble. pero al final hay que cambiar el rodillo. (es necesario medir diariamente los desgastes del rodillo pequeño esto permitirá identificar cual es el punto crítico del desgaste para realizar el cambio de rodillo) seguimos con la zapata grande, su desgaste va cambiando el perfil inicial de la teja, lo primero que provoca es un aumento de espesores en las zonas planas y luego en las curvas , aumentando el peso de la teja, ampliando la anchura de las zonas planas, para ajustar el peso, se baja la zapata con el porta zapatas, pero los desgastes siguen en las zonas planas y curvas va cambiando el perfil y cerrando el espacio/holguras necesario en el montaje de las tejas en el tejado, esto a su vez provoca roturas de las tejas en el tejado por se vuelven rígidas y al pisar las tejas por apalancamiento en el tránsito en el tejado provocan una rotura de las mismas. (es necesario medir diariamente los espesores de las zonas planas y curvas de las tejas y los desgastes de la zapata grande esto permitirá identificar cual es el punto crítico del desgaste para realizar el cambio de la zapata grande) siguen por el rodillo grande, mientras que la 2ª zapata grande pueda funcionar conformando la teja, el rodillo grande no se cambia, pero cada vez más si pierde diámetro el rodillo grande por el desgaste, cada vez tiene que trabajar más la zapata grande para conformar el ensamble. pero al final hay que cambiar el conjunto. (es necesario medir diariamente los desgastes del rodillo grande, esto permitirá identificar cual es el punto crítico del desgaste para realizar el cambio de rodillo) prueba de control de holguras (gaps) de la teja en los ensambles b) discos laterales, guías laterales. un desgaste en cualquier de las piezas mencionadas, causa un “cambio de la medida del perfil inicial en la teja” en este caso es en la anchura de la teja y en el paso de los moldes entre las guías laterales. un desgaste en el disco lateral causa una mala conformación y mayor anchura en los 2 laterales de la teja, provocando un mal acoplamiento de las tejas en el tejado y a su vez roturas de tejas en el tejado. además, la suciedad en los laterales de los moldes causa un mayor desgaste sobre las guías en cada paso por la extrusora, también una mayor necesidad de potencia en la unidad de empuje de los moldes en el paso por la extrusora. (es necesario revisar diariamente los desgastes o deformaciones o adherencias de material en los discos y guías laterales para identificar, cual es el punto crítico del desgaste, deformación o adherencia para realizar el cambio del disco o guía lateral) c) guías de la bancada de la extrusora o cadena empuje. un desgaste, deformación o adherencia en las guías de la bancada, puede provocar un desgaste / deterioro rápido de la base del molde, (pérdida de aluminio de los moldes) problemas de potencia en la unidad de empuje de los moldes en el paso la extrusora. (es necesario revisar diariamente los desgastes o deformaciones o adherencias de material en las guías de la bancada para identificar, cual es el punto crítico del desgaste, deformación o adherencia para realizar el cambio de las guías de la bancada de la extrusora) d) cuchillas corte un desgaste en las cuchillas de corte, causa un cambio de perfil en la parte frontal y trasera de la teja, provoca desgarros de hormigón entre las 2 zonas de la teja con un problema estética/visual de la teja, creando zonas de rebabas en la parte delantera y trasera. por eso se reperfilan las cuchillas de corte hasta que lo permiten sus medidas. (es necesario revisar diariamente los desgastes de la cuchilla para identificar, cual es el punto crítico del desgaste, para reperfilar o cambiar la cuchilla de corte) hasta dónde se llegan a utilizar las cuchillas de corte notas para el video : arganda 141221", "16.Work procedure Wet Tile Measurement Control.pdf": "factory possible work procedure date: 280722 page: 1 of 3 wet tile measurement control n steps drawing key points 1 every 60 minutes we shall take 2 tiles from the line. check the back and lateral side of the mould pallet. 2 every time we take a sample, it shall be placed on the scale to be weighed. once the weight is steady, press the button in the picture to tare the scale. 3 prepare the wet tile to measure its thickness according to the image. tools used: -probe – digital “caliper” -6 x 20 x 200 mm calibrated bar. -10 mm cylindrical bar 200 mm -spatula 4 in order to measure points b, c, d and e we shall use a calibrated bar in order not to deform or vary its measurement. once measured, we shall deduct the 6mm of the bar. take into account the perfect alignment of the caliper with the calibrated bar and its perpendicularity to the mould. 5 in order to measure “0,a” we shall use a cylindrical bar so as not to deform the concrete or vary its measurement. once measured, we shall deduct the 10 mm of the cylindrical bar. take into account the perfect alignment of the caliper with the cylindrical bar and its perpendicularity to the mould. 6 check that the “assemblies” meet the installation standards. measure point “a” and check it is bigger than “b”. this point is critical. if we don’t get a>b, then change the adjusting small slipper. 7 weigh the mould without mixture once the thickness is measured. the weight on the display corresponds to the tile weight. once we weigh the tile, we shall remove the mould and tare the scale to zero. 8 note the results in the extruder control sheet 9 it is necessary to adjust the weights and thicknesses to that established by the central laboratory. if there are variations in the measurements, adjust the extruder head and repeat steps 1- 9 of this procedure. commenting further points (3,4,5) i would propose the following 5 / 7 initial points (a,a1,b,c,d,e,e1) for taking thickness measurements on the tile, always without slurry, then depending on the results, if the measurements of the tile are very constant/repetitive with the same values, you can reduce their time control rate: from hours to days or finally eliminate them, if you consider that they do not contribute anything. the line of measurements should be 100 mm from the front of the tile. for measuring the tops of interlocks a (with 6 mm x 20 mm x 200 mm plate) and a1 (with 10 mm cylindrical bar).", "19.CORNER TILES BREAKAGE ON THE ROOF.pdf": "corner tiles breakage on the roof: in the photos provided of the “corner breakege” tiles on the roof, it is not possible to identify how the tiles are supported by each other and how much slack they have in the assembly. if you can identify a very clearly defined break in the tile, possibly the same length, always the same break line and in the form of an arch (these measurements would have to be checked). all concrete roof tile models already have prefixed \"design\" values with manufacturing thicknesses and manufacturing weights (raw materials and curing) that are the standardised values for the good accommodation of the tile on the roof and values of resistance to bending, once checked the differences between the values given for the thicknesses of the manufactured tiles, it will be possible to make an initial assessment of possible causes of this breakage in the roof: a) if the tile breaks on the roof when walking, i consider that the tile does not support the effort downwards, when stepping on the tile in the centre with the support of the side (possible bad support in the area of assembly in the 2 tiles or lateral contact) and that facilitates making an over lever effort that the tile cannot resist, that area is too critical (fragile) before any value of resistance to bending of the standardised tile. b) if the tile breaks when it is placed on the roof, without additional external stress, it may be because there is already a crack in the tile that facilitates the breakage (when fresh by lifting that area of the tile when cutting the tile or in the curing process due to a shrinkage of the tile in the mould). there is less possibility of tile breakage due to no good support between tiles due to deformations in the aluminium moulds or deformation in the profile in the support area.", "30.Production quality at customer site.pdf": "1 comments aral kiremit (turkey) 240123. dirt on the both sides of the pallets: we continue with the lateral dirt of the pallets, i confirm that there are cleanings by the lateral scrapers in the conveyor of entrance to the extruder, it is not enough. on these 2 scrapers it cleans more residues in the interlocking area than in the overlocking area, i suggest to clean the sides of the pallet at the extruder outlet the lateral guide at the extruder outlet on the overlocking side was replaced because it was broken, in this position in my opinion, although insufficient, it is cleaning the side of the mould with its friction. 2 on the other hand, the other guide in interlocking i think that the level of dirt is the same or worse because of the entrance of the guide. in my opinion, a side scraper should be placed at the extruder outlet or after cutting, on both sides after cutting, with a thin and constant blade. 3 adjustment roller and slipper inclination. the heights of the big roller and the inclination of the pads have been checked again with ibrahim's brother, and after 70,000 tiles have lost (-0.1 to -0.2 mm). we consider that the pallet has a weight difference of 2,420 g / 2,368 gr, and that the loss in curing can vary from 150 gr / 200 gr.( untested) therefore, the dry weight of the tile can vary from 4.5 kg to 4.4 kg, provided that the conditions of the sand mixtures and the humidity of the mixture are maintained. on the subject of the cutting of the tiles, once the mixture of sands was changed and the water in the mixture was increased, it improved and stabilised, what i don't know is the real proportions, the data i have are 900 kg of sand, 295 kg of cement and 6 kg of pigment. the production on the 17th, 18th and 19th of january was very stable, with the consumption of the pallet advancement and the roller remaining stable, with 16.5 a / 16.2 a on the pallet advancement and 11.3 a / 11.4 a on the roller. on the 16th of january until the adjustment of the sand or sand and water mixtures the consumption was 29 a / 23 a at the pallet advancement and 25 a / 17 a at the roller. 4 on the 19th of january when i left, the production at 20:00 was 19.910 tiles and the consumption was 16,5 a for the pallet advancement and 11,5 a for the roller. generation of aluminium waste pallet in the extruder side discs. no aluminium waste was generated today. displacement of the tile mould at the outlet of the fixed bed at the outlet conveyor. in addition to a possible height adjustment of the polycord, the polycord on the overlocking side is impregnated with water and paint which is transferred to it by the polycord of the paint conveyor, which means that it has no traction on this polycord. 5 problems with the cutting of the tiles. this issue has improved, for the 2 reasons i mentioned yesterday, the mixture with more fine sand and more water in the mix: 1) lifting of the central part and the rest of the tile. 2) deterioration of the peak of the overlocking in the cut. 1) lifting of the central part and the rest of the tile. there is hardly any lifting of the front part of the tile, as the penetration of the blade is softer. i still don't know when the cutting blades will arrive. they are in the process of purchasing the equipment to carry out the granulometry and moisture analysis (hopefully soon). 2) deterioration of the overlocking peak in the cut. it has also improved partly because of the previous section and also because the blade no longer cuts the final area of the overlocking tile, separating this final part when the pallets are separated. 6 interlocking stirrers follow the weld of the stirrers well", "31.Tiles production suggestions and methods.pdf": "ackerstein 09/02/22 due to the breakage of sea wave tiles on the roofs, a video call was made on the 9th of february in which a request was made to ackerstein to check the thickness of the tiles and to send 12 tiles to spain and italy. in spain, i work with 3 tiles from each group for the checks. the sea wave tiles, according to the drawing, must have these measurements. it is necessary to achieve e a good coupling between the tiles on the roof tile. the most important measurements are in the \"red circle\" given by the slippers and in the \"green circle\", given by the aluminium mould/pallet: here below the results of the checking of the 6 tiles sent to spain. weights: 3.939 gr. 4.019 gr. 4.002 gr. 4.880 gr. 4,890 gr. 4.916 gr measurements on concrete roof tiles ------------ ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- on aggregates indicate the optimal granulometry in spain and the specific objectives of the sand were. sand prefixed objectives: fineness modul ........................( 2,7 a 3 % ) fines 1 ( 5%)…………………….( 2 a 5 % ) sand equivalent………… …..( 80 al 85 %) ackerstein 21/02/22 in the factory, thickness checks are made on the fresh tiles and depending on the thicknesses in the assembly. i suggested to adjust the thickness of the assembly to 5.7 mm and 11 mm. diameter small roller 119 - diameter big roller 107,65 mm = 11,35 : 2 = 5,7 mm -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- the granulometry of the aggregates indicated can be optimal in spain with the specific objectives. in israel there are very different sands that can give very good results but in some of the sands the moisture they bring is a problem. mixer new recipe sand 430 kg. bazalt 170 kg. cement 52,5 175 kg. water 80 liters. moisture : 8,77 % (8,5 % / 9 % in spain). depends on the aggregates. dry tile 4,576 kg……4,586 kg. objective………….4,398 kg. depends on the aggregates. measures : center of tile….…… 13,23 + 14 (27,23)…….12,75+ 13 (25,75)…… 13,4 + 14 (27,4) “objective”………..26 mm(-1,23)....…..25 mm(-0,75)……….26(-1,4) mm interlock…………….…11,18 ( 11)……………...5,3 /6 ( 5,7) )…………. 8,75 (7,9) “objective”………..11 mm(+0,18)…….5,7 mm. (-0,4)………7,9(-0,85) mm ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- regarding the problem of the possible difference in the profile of the steel slipper (may- october) and the widia slipper / tungsten (november-february), the drawings of the two slipper are requested. the steel slipper corresponds to the drawing 1777-013. the widia/tungsten slipper corresponds to the drawing 1777-023. these are the same dimensions “as the steel slipper”. ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- meeting with adam to evaluate the various types of the available sands in order to further adjust the mix to the granulometric curve presented. tests with different sands are planned for 22 february 2022. ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- ackerstein 22/02/22 first test of new aggregates with more basalt sand, it gets a better surface appearance, but it comes wetter and the amount of water has to be reduced. mixer recipe sand 400 kg. bazalt 200 kg. ( high humidity) cement 52,5 175 kg. water 80 liters. (75/80) fresh tile fresh tile measure: 4,780 kg. ( 7480 – 2,700 mould ) test with sea sand second test with sea sand, but being that was not possible to control the excess of humidity generated with the sands, the test has stopped immediately. ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- i suggested a daily check of the weights and thicknesses of the tiles, every 1 or 2 hours, that should be carried out with the new measurement tools. ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- i suggested in the extruder place one more stirrer in front of the junction of the big and small slipper. --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- after control of the results dry tile in the laboratory, the adjustment of the thickness of the tile about production 23 february, i suggested, to lower the thickness on both sides of the big slipper by “ 0.5 mm”. ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- ackerstein 23/02/22 in the morning, revision of the extruder box : a new stirrer is placed in the interlock side, shifted 5 mm to the left, all stirrer positions are identified, the lengths of the limiters and the roller diameters are checked. during extruder box set-up, i have identified that for better settings of rollers and slipper a metal bar should be used between the two guides of the bench. ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- i suggested the use of a metal bar (300 x 100 x 5 mm) to make all the adjustments the extruder needs. video uno 10 extruder settings has been provided to customer, with addiotional notes in a separate document. ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- the small roller has excessive wear on the large roller side. d ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- i suggest a daily control of the extruder situation (rollers,slippers, stirrers, limiters) that is necessary to improve the tile forming process. it is necessary to identify the duration of the “big and small roller steel” and “big and small slipper widia”, to avoid making the concrete tile incorrectly ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- i suggest the control and monitoring of the mixer. --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- meeting with charlie and adam about the curing chambers, the cycle that is used in spain and the possibilities for changes that can be made to the current curing chambers. for the chamber curing process, i suggest : a) placing a system of pipes and extractors on the roof of the chamber to extract excess humidity above 98 %. b) install hot air pipes with diffusers in the lower parts of the chambers to cause an envelope in all the tile rackers, so that they try to equalise the chamber temperature at all heights, thereby ensuring better curing. for the paint application process, i suggest : the heating of the paint to better polymerise the application, a drying tunnel at the outlet of the application and a line of high-flow downstream fans to better distribute the paint in the central parts of the concrete tile. ackerstein 24/02/22 fresh tiles production 240222 measures : center of tile….…… 13,15 + 14 (27,15)…….12,75+ 13 (25,75)…… 13,4 + 14 (27,4) “objective”………..26 mm(-1,15)....…..25 mm(-0,75)……….26(-1,4) mm interlock…………….…11,5 ( 11)………………...6 ( 5,7) )…………….…. 8,75 (7,9) “objective”………..11 mm(+0,5)…….5,7 mm. (-0,3)………7,9(-0,85) mm measuring tiles in laboratory -dry tile production 230222 (17 hours after curing) strengh : 2.415 n. weight: 4,628 kg. measures : center of tile….…… 13,2 + 14 (27,2)…….12,75+ 13 (25,75)…… 13,7 + 14 (27,4) “objective”………..26 mm(-1,2)....…..25 mm(-0,75)……….26(-1,7) mm after check of the results on dry tiles, i suggested to lower the thickness only on the “wave” side of the big slipper by “ 0.5 mm”. interlock……………...…11 ( 11)………………...6 ( 5,7) )……………...…. 8 (7,9) “objective”………..11 mm()………..….5,7 mm. (+0,3)………7,9(-0,1) mm ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- at the moment the measurements of the interlock are correct according to the drawing, regarding the measurements in the centre of the tile, i suggest that they should be reduced from 13 mm to 12.5 mm and maintain a minimum of 12.5 mm in the centre of the tile, as all the sections are not equal in their compactions, so a minimum of “12.5” mm of section should be admitted. once the 13 mm / 12.5 mm / 13 mm measurements are stabilised, after 4 weeks of production and it can be demonstrated by the process sheets extruder and tests, that their weights and resistances are maintained, the following test can be considered to reduce the size of the tile to 12.5 mm / 12 mm / 12.5 mm. all changes of extruder settings should be made very slowly to check the results as sands and moistures change the tile dimensions and properties. meeting 14:00 an assessment is made of what has been done and what has been commented on during the period of action from 21 to 24 february 2022 in the factory and possible future actions. a) the details of the revisions of the roof tiles sent to spain were assessed, regarding the thickness and appearance of the roof tile surfaces. there is a requirement to fit the tiles on the roof, which, if the measurements of the assembly are not adequate, can cause breakage of the tiles on the roof due to poor support of one tile with the other. there is a big difference between the reference thicknesses according to the drawing and the actual thicknesses of the tiles. the oscillations in the weights and thicknesses are caused by the sands, as they change the density of the concrete, but the weights with the same mixture of sands should not vary more than 50/100 grams. regarding the surfaces of the tiles, in my assessment i have had missing information on when they could be generated, in the extrusion or by paint applications. b) it has been commented on the profile of the tile produced from (may to october) and that of (november to february) and it has been stated that on the drawings provided 1777-013 and 1777-023, that there is a constant profile sea wave in the big and small steel and widia slippers supplied. d) the values of the optimum sand in spain and the possible mixtures in the sands of israel have been assessed, therefore some tests have been planned and carried out to identify if there is a possible better mixture of the current sands. the need for a good screening of the sand has been identified by finding in the body of the tile at the exit of the extrusion large stones and conglomerates of the dune sand, which generate expansions on the surface of the tile at the exit of the big slipper. in my experience with screens, i have had the best results with liwell screens and with mixer with eirich rv. the following components must be available for sand installations: a moisture controller in the lower parts of the silos to deliver the kilos of sand we need, discounting the kilos of water for the moisture of the sand, and a moisture controller in the mixer. e) regarding the wear of the extruder elements, i have indicated an estimated minimum and maximum duration of wear, which is always determined by the types of sand used. the table on the estimated wear of each part of the extruder has been provided to adam. a possible change to be considered would be the use of the small widia roller with the aim of changing the shaft as little as possible with the new rollers. on average, a complete change of roller assembly for maintenance and for replace the parts with new ones takes around 3-4 hours, you can consider an entire morning to be on the safe side. further information on others customers that produce seawave tiles’ criterias for replacing slippers and rollers will be given once collected. f) in my opinion, in order to make progress in the production of a quality tile, it is necessary to carry out rigorous process controls of the tile from the mixer, extruder, oil application, paint application, racker stacking, tile curing in the chambers, racker unstacking, demoulding, dry paint application, paint drying, stacking, packaging and palletising, etc. the more processes can be controlled, the more process improvements can be planned, which will lead to improvements for a higher quality roof tile and higher customer satisfaction. g) about the extruder the current operating conditions must be known, i have only identified the speed of the roller 160 r.pm and that the possible height of the big slipper is 32 mm, there is no further precision knowing the inclination of the slippers. the big roller already has a wear in its diameters of 2 mm and the small roller already has a deformation in the plane between the two rollers. h) ) it is insisted on the necessity to control the critical adjustments in the measures in the assembly 5,7 / 11 mm and in the parts of the centre of the tile (13 / 12,5 / 13 mm) and lateral wave of 7,9 mm to assure the best support of the tiles in the roof. considerations on the future of the thicknesses in the tile, it is necessary to maintain the measures of the possible assembly of the tile and to progress in reducing the measures of the thickness of the centre of the tile, from my point of view it can be possible to arrive at the values of 12,5 / 12/ 12,5 mm (according to mixture of sands) can arrive at its limit, assuring that these thicknesses maintain the good values of resistance to flexion and support the effort on the transit of people on the roof. i) we reviewed approaches to improvements in the curing of the chambers and assisting in the drying of the paint on the dry roof tiles. j) finally, assemblies were made with tiles produced last year and this week's tiles, it was found that the old tiles do not support enough for the measurements of the assembly as the ones made this week. in my opinion, tiles from different productions should not be mixed and the longer the time they spend curing in the yard, the more the possibility of breakage in the roof will be reduced. ashdod 24/02/22", "5.Notes on efflorescence.pdf": "efflorescence in concrete roof tile generally, the occurrence of white spots on the surface of concrete products is called efflorescence. in concrete roof tiles, during production processes can appear changes in tile surface, among them an uniformed whitening, various white dots with different diameter and irregular spots, all of these can be called efflorescence. the efflorescence always prejudice the appearance and the color of the concrete tiles . all these distinguishing marks show up mainly in the external surface of the tile and can be produced when the humidity dissolves the soluble compounds (sulphates, carbonates, silicates, chlorides, nitrates, etc) from concrete tile body and carry them to the surface where they react with the air and, in some extreme cases, by evaporating they leave a mineral deposit (crystalline salts), usually is calcium carbonate. caco₃ it is necessary that all the mixing components (sand, water, pigment) have the less quantity of calcium, independent of that provided by the cement itself, in order to avoid the creation of soluble compounds that can develop in efflorescence. the main types of efflorescence are the following: 1. primary efflorescence - an uniformed whitening of tile surface can be caused by an inappropriate curing cycle to the tiles (with curing chambers or tunnels) that can blanch the colour tonality and is identified at the exit of the curing chambers or tunnels. 2. condensing efflorescence – a lot of small white dots on tile surface, that can correspond to cold or too warm areas and that are created during the curing process. this is identified at the exit of the curing chambers or tunnels. 3. frontal/rear efflorescence with isolated spots on the surface. this efflorescence can be generated during cutting process due to the water spraying to clean the blades that can generate a humidity excess, that can be detected after the curing, at the exit of the curing chambers or tunnels. 4. efflorescence on upper & lower tile surfaces that appear when the tiles are on the yard or when already installed on the roof, that appear with very intense white spots, calcium carbonate. this is the most extreme form of efflorescence with the process of carbonization (chemical reaction where the calcium hydroxide reacts with carbon dioxide and forms insoluble calcium carbonate form: ca(oh)₂ + co₂ → caco₃ + h₂o). it appears just during some periods of the year with extreme weather conditions, like heavy rain, stagnant water, cold temperatures, strong changes heat / cold, condensation, snow, dew. the efflorescence varies a lot in its speed and shape depending on the humidity levels. the possibility of having efflorescence on the tile surface is correlated to the application of the acrylic sealer before the tiles packing. how to prevent or reduce efflorescence on the tiles: the first things that helps to avoid efflorescence is the usage of washed sands, with a good granulometry and portland cement with low-grade of alkalies in order to have a mixing with low water absorption. if, using the best raw materials possible, the problem with efflorescence persists on the upper or lower surfaces, we should try to minimize the effects at least on the upper surface that is the visible part on a roof. tile upper surface: in order to avoid efflorescence on that area is essential to apply an acrylic sealer on the entire upper/outer surface of the cured tile after depalletting and before packing. also wrapping the tiles packages helps to preserve the tiles surface form the formation of efflorescence. tile lower surface: in order to reduce efflorescence on lower surface of the tile it is important to avoid the water absorption in the concrete mix and this can be reached putting an additive (waterproofing) that can reduce/eliminate the penetration of water into the body of the tile, blocking the pores of the concrete in order to reduce that the soluble salts come out to the tile surface. miguel blanes canut.", "13.Pushing system maintenance.pdf": "pag. 1 complete pushing system maintenance description of operations description 1) mark and disassemble the trolleys. take out all 9 trolleys. pag. 2 description 2) replace bearings, shafts and polycords of the trolleys. check the condition of the trolleys by changing bearings and pushers if necessary. description 3) replace bearings, shafts and polycords of the trolleys. pag. 3 replace bearings, shafts and polycords. pag. 4 description 3) disassemble of the pushing chain by unbuttoning the saddle or ½ connecting link. pag. 5 description 4) change the double chain sections, connecting links and saddles (shown in the video). description 5) cleanwash bench and pushing chain structure. pag. 6 pushing system without double chain and trolleys, ready to wash with pressure water. pushing system washed. description 6) change the pushing chain guides. in case of excessive wear, all the guides of the push chain must be replaced. pag. 7 guides replacement: pag. 8 description 7) disassemble pushing chain gearbox. check the clearance of the drive sprocket with a new section of chain → if there is excess clearance the drive sprocket and shaft must be replaced. disconnect the motor electrically & take reference of the electrical connection. pag. 9 empty the gearbox of oil and take out the electric motor. mark the bearing covers on each side, remove the one on the rod side of the cutting carriage. the gearbox unit cannot be removed from the sprocket drive shaft. unscrew the bearing cover on the gearbox unit side and remove the gearbox unit with the sprocket drive shaft. pag. 10 dissamble the gearbox unit with the sprocket drive shaft. description 8) disassemble the sprocket shaft of the drive side in an external workshop. replace the sprocket drive shaft with the gearbox unit in an external workshop to dissamble it with a hydraulic press, use it to replace the bearings in the bearing cover on the gearbox unit side and replace the new sprocket drive shaft. old sprocket drive shaft disassembled pag. 11 description 9) assemble the gearbox unit and the new sprocket shaft of the pushing chain. assemble the gearbox unit with the new sprocket drive shaft on the pushing chain bench. assemble the bearing covers on both sides. pag. 12 assemble of the electric motor and oil refill of the gearbox. pag. 13 description 10) assemble the new double chain and the trolleys. assemble and fasten the new double pushing chain assemble the 9 trolleys on the double pushing chain. assemble upper mould guides on the pushing chain. pag. 14 new double pushing chain tensioned with the 9 trolleys. description 11) assemble the extruder head. assemble the extruder head on the bench. pag. 15 12) start moulds through the pushing chain and check the pusher plate push in the mould. start the moulds step through the pushing chain and check the moulds push by the pusher plate. description 13) synchronize the cutting system point of the tile. pag. 16 place the cutting system at the central point of its displacement and the mould with its push chain in the central area (its cutting position), cutting blades perpendicular to the bench. place the rod of the cutting system at the upper point of the wheel and adjust the cutting system arm for that distance with the centered cutting system.", "2.Cleaning pallets.pdf": "*** cleaning moulds. depending on the amount of adhesions and where it is, various kind of cleaning can be recommended. initially for small quantities of molds with small adhesions cleaning can be performed manually (screwdriver or similar). if the quantities of moulds are large and the adhesions cleaning can be done with a high pressure water pump or in the last case with sandblast. how to clean the sides of the mould in wet after the extruder? an alternative can be :", "24.Maintenance flow charts.pdf": "", "37.Extruder machine maintenance excursus.pdf": "1 onur kiremit manufacturing equipment of roof tiles may 2023 2 concrete conveyor to the extruder box the mixture exit of the hopper must be adjusted, so that it works with more or less quantity at the entrance of the hopper of the extruder, depending on the speed of the production line. it is necessary to balance the amount of mixture to the belt that feeds the extruder to avoid the constant operation of the feeding belt, since in this way it is not possible to maintain a constant level in the extruder box. for a better performance of this conveyor, it should be slow in a normal and constant feed to always maintain the same feed column and also have a fast speed when there is no mixture in the conveyor to avoid production stops in the factory due to lack of mixture in the extruder box. it must be guaranteed that the entrance of concrete into the hopper of the extruder incurs its majority in the area of consumption of the same since otherwise vaults will be formed and the concrete will not flow in the feeding zone of the corresponding rollers and slippers. clear example of centering the entrance of mortar in the area of consumption. 3 place a metal detector to prevent the entry of metal parts in the extruder conveyor. (improvement) (future investment if tc roller and slipper will be used) the scraper does not work well is fixed (deterioration of the rubber band and mixture fall to the ground, it is necessary that the scraper is mobile and maintain the pressure for cleaning the mortar band. to clean the band, a scraper with \"tensioners\" in the center of the drum and perpendicular is better. tensioners : 4 manufacturing equipment of roof tiles this machine, being the most complex as a whole, has been distributed in the following zones or equipment: *pallets pushing system, extrusion head, bench & removable bench guides.(bench guides) *pallets pushing system. *extrusion head “double roman” *electromechanical cutter “double roman” pallets pushing system,extrusion head,bench & removable bench guides. it is important to maintain in good condition the bench guides, both the lower (all horizontal and aligned guides) and the lateral ones (all vertical and aligned guide)., of the 3 sets where they are located, the pallets aluminium must pass through the guides of these 3 positions well aligned and favouring the entry in the passages of the pushing system to the extrusion head and in turn to the cutter , any difference in the guides can cause a deformation or wear to the moulds in their passage. 5 all guides on the bench guides must be kept in good condition and replaced when necessary. pallets pushing system. the pushing system chain is not bad in appearance, the trolley polycores need to be adapted, but the measurements between the pusher fingers are very bad, the initial measurement of this distance is 420 mm, currently most of them have 424 mm between the pusher fingers, the chain and couplings in use have generated a stretching of the chain of about 4 mm, so you can identify a gap of “4 mm” between pallets when pushing the chain. it is recommended to replace the pusher chain if there are synchronisation problems with the “cutting of the tile” or if the distance between its fingers has reached 425 mm, at the same time replace all the bearings and identify if the drive sprocket is worn or not, in case it is necessary to replace it at the same time as the chain. 6 replace trolley bearings. replace pushing tooth bearings. if worn or loose, replace the chain drive sprocket. pushing system trolleys polycors ( measurements of polycors) a 9 mm b 8 mm c 8 mm 7 check the chain tension measurements periodically, on both sides equally. 8 extrusion head this is the main equipment in the manufacture of concrete roof tiles and where the right settings are needed to achieve a quality tile with the mix produced by the mixer. in the event of a mix with errors in the additions of raw materials or problems with moisture or problems with the height adjustments of the rollers and slippers, this equipment can suffer high compressions, pressures, tensions and wear between its elements (rollers, slippers, stirrers, shafts, bearings, sprockets, chains) when producing concrete tiles the 2 problems with the rollers in the extruder and the space that occurs in the assembly of the big and small slipper in the slipper support are discussed in a special annex. 9 extrusion head process sheet starting from the premise that we are going to manufacture concrete roof tiles in the extruder with an initial mix of pre-set characteristics (sand, cement, pigment, water, additive and with a humidity that we intend to be stable), it is necessary to establish some values for adjusting the rollers/slippers, the speeds of the rollers and stirrers and the rest of the extrusion values, which we indicate in our process sheet, to serve as a basis for identifying what is generated by any change in the variables that we can modify with the aim of improving the quality of the tile and always producing within the control values of the process sheet. the extruder process sheet that i am going to present consists of 17 indicators that i consider \"necessary to take into account\", in order to control the whole \"extruder process sheet\". (after the implementation of the process sheet and the monitoring of its indicators, it can be assessed whether any of the 17 indicators do not need to be monitored.) in the development of this process, each factory can expand or reduce the proposed indicators as they see fit. 1 r.p.m. 2 r.p.m. 3 mm 4 mm 5 mm 6 big roller to big slipper \"gap\" (d) mm 7 small slipper inclination ( + 2 mm) mm 8 mm 9 mm 10 mm 11 mm 12 ºc 13 ºc 14 ampere 15 ampere 16 mm 17 t.p.m tiles per minute pushing chain ammeter column height. maximum slipper temperature roller ammeter height distance between big and small slippers maximum roller temperature new roller diameter. used roller diameter. limiters length . ( policord)) steel extruder box roller speed. star bar speed. roller height.(a) slipper entry height (b) slipper exit height.(c) factory: onur seccion : extruder box process : head extrusion / double roman profile nº parameters nominal value minimum value maximum value units notes process sheet code 2023 review number: page: 1 10 there are 4 main indicators in this process, which are the measures of adjustment of the tile head, a, b, c and d, they are very particular for each model of tile and conditioned to the raw materials (mixture) that are used for the manufacture of the tile. the measurements \"a\", \"b\", \"c\" and \"d\" correspond to: \"a\" = distance from the bench guides to the flat areas of the roller, according to the thickness of the tile in the flat area minus the height of the mould. \"b\" = distance from the bench guides to the big slipper entrance. \"c\" = distance from the bench guides to the exit of the big slipper. (\"track slipper inclination mm\" = b - c) \"d\" = distance from the big slipper to the big roller \"gap d\". initially for measures b, c and d, there are reference values, as detailed in the table below, always depending on the type of sand (fine / coarse) used. 11 there is also an initial reference roller speed, the calculation values are the speed (tiles/minute) and the smallest roller diameter of the tile profile. however, once in production with the other settings, it can vary, any excess of the roller speed will result in increased wear of the roller the 17 indicators presented in this process sheet are possible or indicative values, each of which must be confirmed during the production of roofing tiles to validate that they meet the objectives set . to understand a little more about the shaping of the tile on a mould, the philosophy is to overfeed concrete into the space between the mould and the roller / slipper, to maintain a fresh concrete on the pallet at a certain compaction, so that it does not deform during the whole process of cutting, moving and stacking. 1 r.p.m. 2 r.p.m. 3 mm 4 mm 5 mm 6 big roller to big slipper \"gap\" (d) mm 7 small slipper inclination ( + 2 mm) mm 8 mm 9 mm 10 mm 11 mm 12 ºc 13 ºc 14 ampere 15 ampere 16 mm 17 t.p.m check check check tiles per minute 50 48 52 pushing chain ammeter 11,5 10 17 check column height. 500 450 600 check maximum slipper temperature 30 20 35 roller ammeter 16,5 15 23 check height distance between big and small slippers 3,5 3,0 4,0 check maximum roller temperature 35 20 50 check check new roller diameter. 134 133,8 134 check used roller diameter. 127 126 128 check 2,5 2 3 2 1,5 2,5 limiters length . ( policord)) 120 100 150 slipper entry height (b) 37,6 32 36 check slipper exit height.(c) 39,6 33 38 check 110 130 check star bar speed. 140 130 150 check roller height.(a) 36,6 31 35 check process sheet code 11/05/2023 review number: page: 1 factory: onur seccion : extruder box process : head extrusion / double roman profile nº parameters nominal value minimum value maximum value units notes steel extruder box roller speed. 120 12 all the mixture from the hopper supported on the base of the pallet, is fed by the pallet itself towards the roller assisted by the rotation of the roller, in that direction with an initial leakage of concrete between the roller and slipper. at this point there are already more process indicators, which intervene for this shaping, the height of the mixture column in the hopper (mm), the speed of the roller (rpm), units / dimensions of the stirrers and their speed (rpm), mixture limiters in the flat areas of the tile (yes / no) (length mm). 13 actions / notes plan actions / notes n.4 central adjustment bolts for inclination. ( big slipper) n.2 (left)+ n.2 (right) adjustment bolts for high / low setting. (big and small) slippers. n.1 (left)+ n.1 (right) front adjustment bolts for horizontal setting, to close the gap between the slipper and the roller: gap “d” (see sop 260 and sop 270). unscrew for spacing from roller, screw to come near. small slipper (see yellow bold circle): n.2 adjustment bolts for inclination and high / low setting. n.1 nut for horizontal setting to close the gap between the small slipper and the small roller. setting of slipper and small slipper the adjusment bolts / nuts 1 2 3 4 2 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 2 3 4 2 1 3 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 14 actions / notes plan actions / notes 1) the gap “d” allows the small recirculation of the concrete, reducing the pressure in the extrusion slipper and it determines the right compaction of the concrete to produce the roof tiles. 2) it is important to check visually the measure of the gap “d”. 3) the visual check has to be made in the flat space between the slipper and the roller, right and left sides. ( see image blue circle). 4) to visual check it is necessary a mirror with a light: (see next sop 280). 5) the measure of the flat space between the slipper and the roller vary, according to the mix wet or dry, from 1 to 5 mm. 6) to settle the gap “d” unscrew/ screw the n.1(left)+ n.1(right) ront adjustment bolts of the slipper unit. unscrew for spacing from roller, screw to come near. (see sop 250). 7) the small recirculation of the concrete, taking out the pressure in the extrusion slipper is also obtained with the grinding of the slipper and of the small slipper and with the polycord rope the quality control on diameter of 20 mm positioned the roof tiles determine inside the extrusion head. the setting of the (see sop 280 and 290). gap “d”. setting of slipper : the gap \"d\" 1 2 3 4 2 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 2 3 4 2 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 15 actions / notes plan actions / notes to check the measure of the gap “d”: 1) light with a torch the roller and slipper from the top. (see image blue circle). 2) put the welding mirror under the roller. be careful, the space is narrow. (see image red circle). 3) the welding mirror reflect gap “d”. (see image red circle). 4) it is important to verify that the light reflected of the gap “d” has the same thickness because the flat space between the slipper and the roller, right and left sides, must be in parallelism. the check is visual. (see sop 260). 5) to be sure to set in the same way right and left sides, unscrew/ screw the n.1 (right) front adjustment bolt of the slipper unit, measure the horizontal setted displacement with a venier (see image with the yellow arrow) and do the same for the n.1 (left) front adjustment bolt. 6) be careful, the screw of the (right/left) front adjustment bolt of the slipper unit, to come near the roller with the slipper, is suggested to be done with setting of 0,5 mm each time ! the contact of the slipper with the roller can damage the slipper. the quality control on the roof tiles determine the setting of the gap “d”. check and set the gap \"d\" 1 2 3 4 2 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 2 3 4 2 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 1 3 16 this video from vortex has been provided, where all the phases of the roller and slipper adjustment are identified. 17 in addition, it is necessary to monitor the thickness and weights of the wet and dry tiles, the controls should initially be \"every hour\" (after the implementation of the thickness control, the appropriate frequency of monitoring should be assessed), as there are many fluctuations in the mixture due to the sand or water in the mixture, in the case of the dry tiles it can be started every 2 hours and then, depending on the results, adjusted to the best needs. wet and dry tiles. i have varied my initial approach, leaving 6 points of control in the wet tile and another 6 points in the dry tile, the ranges of measures are the initial ones, after the verifications it will be necessary to determine when it is superior to the maximum value the actions to carry out in the extruder. wet double roman tile measures : regarding the control of the measurements of the wet tile, i consider that they can be considered according to the points indicated in the photo. the suggested thicknesses can be wdr1 to wdr6 at 65mm from the end of the tile. these measurements should be checked again, as they are quite different from the initial theoretical measurements, it may be an error in the reading on the caliper, due to the mixture with the accelerator or the measurements of the slipper. double roman wet tile measures wdr1 wdr2 wdr3 wdr4 wdr5 wdr6 11,5 13 13 13 9,6 7,6 initial vortex 12,5 11,69 11,2 11,39 11,22 7,9 mr.murat check range 11....12 12,5....13,512,5....13,512,5....13,5 9,1….10,1 7…..8,1 date: dd-mm-yy 4,7….4,6 kg. time weight 12,50 10,75 11,20 11,10 11.8 8,00 4,44 mr.murat 12,52 11,69 11,18 11,39 11,22 7,90 4,70 check 4,32 4,50 18 wet weight tile factory-tested tile weights from 4.28 kg to 4.7 kg. are due to the use of accelerator in the mixture, with these differences in weights it is difficult to determine which weight should be considered as the target weight in the process sheet. in a mixture without accelerator, the theoretical wet weight of the tile,on the curing weight loss ( 150 g/200 g) , initially 4.7 kg to 4.6 kg to achieve a tile weight after curing of 4.4 kg to 4.5 kg. dry double roman measures : suggested thicknesses can be ddb1 to ddb6 at 65mm from the end of the tile. the measurement ranges are the initial ones, after the verifications it will be necessary to determine when it is superior to the maximum value the actions to be carried out in the extruder on the wet tile. i don't have measurements of the dry tile, you have to make them and check what differences there are and what are the objective values for the process sheet. roller and pallet pushing amperage control i don't have amperage measurements of the pusher chain and roller, you have to identify them on the control screen and check what the differences are and what the target values are for the process sheet. the theoretical amperage consumption in the thrust train under normal circumstances should be 16,5 a (pallet pushing system) and 11.5 a for the roller. double roman dry tile measures ddr1 ddr2 ddr3 ddr4 ddr5 ddr6 drawing 5 11,5 26 26 3,5 11 initial vortex mr.murat check range 5....6 11....12 26....27 26....27 3,5…3 11…..11,5 date: dd-mm-yy 4,4….4,5 mr.murat time weight check 19 roller and slipper wear control. in relation to the established rule on wear, for 1 big roller, 2 small rollers, 2 big slipper and 4 small slippers are consumed. it is necessary to carry out an initial control, every 2 days, depending on the production carried out. progressively, if it is of interest, a longer period of time between controls can be considered, depending on the wear control. big / small roller double roman wear measures : planned control points wsr 1 to wbr7, starting with the small roller (interlocking) and ending with the big roller (overlocking). these measurements should be checked again, as they are very different from the initial theoretical measurements of the vortex /big / small roller), it may be an error in the gauge reading or the manufacture of the rollers to different measurements to the original vortex ones. big / small roller double roman wear measures wsr1 wsr2 wbr3 wbr4 wbr5 wbr6 wbr7 rollers new 122 126 134 84 134 85 114 initial vortex 11/05/2023 120,2 126 130,3 80,9 130,3 85 106 mr.murat check range 134...126 134...126 date time 20 big / small slipper double roman wear measures : planned control points wss 1 to wbs 10, starting with the small slipper (interlocking) and ending with the big slipper (overlocking). it is necessary to check all the initial measurements, because the slippers are fixed to slipper supports, which are in most cases the reference points of measurement. these measurements should be checked again, as they are very different from the initial theoretical measurements of the vortex /big / small slipper), it may be an error in the gauge reading or the manufacture of the slippers to different measurements to the original vortex ones. big / small lipper double roman wear measures wss1 wss2 wbs3 wbs4 wbs5 wbs6 wbs7 wbs8 wbs9 wbs10 initial slippers new 53 6 4 40 15,5 24,5 40 14,5 25,5 29,5 vortex 11/05/2023 52,26 5,56 3,03 40 0 32,6 40 0 24,9 22,1 mr.murat range check date time 21 stirrers and limiters stirrer pin function: feed the roller with concrete in the complicated areas (curved) of the tile. the stirrer pin must avoid the creation of vaults when the concrete enters the roller. it’s common to adjust the stirrer pin to the tile sides, since the interlocking area usually has low thickness in the tile or in the area of the roller’s smaller diameter. i suggest to distribute the stirrer pins in such a way that they feed more the curved areas, because the flat areas are less necessary. limiters function: the limiter polycors must hold the ingress of concrete in certain areas to avoid feed excess which later gives way to a compaction excess. the purpose of the limiters polycors is to try to achieve the same pressure/compaction along the entire tile cutting line. i suggest with the new distribution of stirrers is to halve the length of the limiters, in case of excessive pressure in the flat areas, you would have to go back to the original length or longer. 22 electromechanical cutter “double roman” attention must be paid to the sliding guides and the sliding guides of the cutter. it is not recommended to clean the cutting carriage contour with high pressure water. the carriage and cutting slide shafts must be kept clean and periodically lubricated.", "40.Tensioning the push chain 240925.pdf": "1 tensioning the push chain regarding your question, there is indeed a standard or tolerance that i use for chain tensioning, based on the design philosophy of its components. however, in this case, it is not possible to measure with a caliper. a) initial tensioning with the lateral tensioners: first, the chain must be tensioned using the lateral tensioners. b) bilateral tension verification: on both sides equally (right and left, in the direction of the mold movement), the chain tension is checked by pressing the outer chain inward. this verifies if there is any play or wobble when trying to bring one chain closer to the other. once confirmed that there is no play and the chain is considered properly tensioned, the final tension measurement from both sides should be recorded for reference. 2 c) final check under actual operating conditions: the definitive verification is performed with the chain moving under production load. the goal is to confirm that the belleville washers are fulfilling their function as dynamic damping elements. to do this.  action: place your hand on the belleville washer stack.  expected result: you should feel a slight, cyclic compression and decompression as the chain advances. this indicates that the washers are absorbing load variations and maintaining constant tension.  sign of a problem (over-tensioning): if the washers are completely rigid and show no movement, it signifies over- tensioning. this nullifies their function, puts excessive mechanical stress on the chain and bearings, and demands more work from the motor. in this case, it is necessary to loosen the tension slightly.", "0 Checklist MTO PVO IBF Cadena Empuje LIST 220925 1943.pdf": "list (22-09-2025) machine type: tm-101 serial number: m.02540 a.1.1. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 section item verification frequency a. keep - cleanliness & visual inspection 1 general cleanliness of the pushing unit daily daily: it must not be changed. air gun. b.2.1. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 section item chains and trolleys cleaning frequency based on the amount of dirt accumulated b. clean - cleaning tasks 1 air gun + degreaser + cleaning rags + after weekly on the chain, guides, and bearings. the initially established lubrication frequency is weekly. ptfe spray lubricant (w40 or similar ) chains trolley 1 b.2.2. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 section item verify/check deterioration frequency b. clean - clean + check 2 load-bearing guide rails weekly weekly: it must not be changed. tactile check: (must be clean) right upper guide b.2.3. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 section item verify/check deterioration frequency b. clean - clean + check 3 pulleys and chains weekly weekly: it must not be changed. tactile check: (must be clean) chains trolley 1-2 b.2.4. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 section item verify/check deterioration frequency b. clean - cleaning + check 4 bearings and trolleys axles weekly weekly: it must not be changed. tactile check: (must be clean) bearings trolley 1 b.2.5. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 section item verify/check deterioration frequency b. clean - clean + check 5 trolleys plaques for tooths weekly weekly: it must not be changed. tactile check: (must be clean) right plaque trolley 1 c.2.6. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 section item manual verification and condition assessment frequency c. check 6 anti -lift device molds weekly weekly: it must not be changed. tactile check: (must be clean) duroglis d.2.7. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 section item identification of trolley lubrication points frequency based on the consumption rate of grease d. lubrication 7 trolleys grease fittings weekly applied to axles and bearings . the initially established lubrication frequency is weekly. grease fitting 1 e.2.8. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 section item identification of molds lubrication points. frequency based on the incidences that the nozzles e. lubrication 8 lubrication system for mold guides weekly have in that application the initially established lubrication frequency is weekly. oil nozzle 1 m.3.1. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 section item verify/check measurements frequency based on the progression of slack created d. special check - measurements & tracking 1 chain elongation measurement monthly in the joints or the stretching of the chain. the initially established measure frequency is monthly. measure with a large analog or digital calliper. trolley 1 m.3.2. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 section item verify/check measurements frequency based on the progression of slack created d. special check - measurements & tracking 2 chain tension in tensioning links monthly in the joints or the stretching of the chain. the initially established measure frequency is monthly. measure with a large analog or digital calliper. washers m.3.3. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 section item verify/check measurements frequency based on the polycord wear progression d. special check - measurements & tracking 3 polycord wear (trolleys 1-9) monthly the initially established measure frequency is monthly. measure with a small analog or digital calliper. policord 1", "Checklist MTO PVO IBF Cadena Empuje A.1.1 230925 1943.pdf": "a.1.1. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 • equipment: m.02540 • frequency: daily • inspector: ___________________ • date: //_______ main checklist table: section item verification frequency ✅ complies ❌ fails observations/measurement a. keep - cleanliness & visual inspection 1 general cleanliness of the pushing unit daily air gun. trolley 1 trolley 2 note: trolley 3 before starting the surface cleaning with the air gun, check for aluminum mold residue on top of the trolley 4 chain and on the surface or sides of the trolley plaques. trolley 5 1. air cleaning: criteria: trolley 6 blow top surfaces of plaques and chain of 9 trolleys. no accumulation of thick dust/grease. trolley 7 blow around the central bearing. no compacted residue. trolley 8 trolley 9 chains 1 / 9 plaques 1 / 9 bearings 1 / 9 guides frame duroglis observations & corrective actions: air gun: • material: aisi 316 stainless steel, peek plastic. o nozzles: flat venturi (low contamination) o flow rate: 10-15 liters per minute o precise angulation (15°-25°) 3. quick visual inspection after cleaning: criteria: 3. immediate actions: - condition of trolley plaques. no visible cracks or deformations. if aluminum residue, severe scoring, or a locked bearing is detected: - central bearing. rotates freely, no abnormal noises. 1. record in detail the affected trolley and issue in the checklist. - lateral scoring on plates or structure. no deep marks or exposed metal. 2. immediately report to the production/maintenance manager before the end of the shift. - aluminum residue (white/silver dust). absence of chips or metallic powder. 3. photograph the defect (if possible) for attached documentation. 4. jointly assess urgency for the next day: o high priority: schedule preventive maintenance before restarting production. o medium priority: plan repair in the next maintenance window. notes: · the inspection is performed with the line stopped at the end of production. · no disassembly is required, but agile communication between shifts is essential for traceability. · the goal is to prevent mold damage and accelerated wear through planned actions.", "Checklist MTO PVO IBF Cadena Empuje B.2.1 220925 1943.pdf": "b.2.1. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 • equipment: m.02540 • frequency: weekly • inspector: ________________ • date: //___________________ main checklist table: section item chains and trolleys cleaning frequency ✅ complies ❌ fails observations/measurement b. clean - cleaning tasks 1 air gun + degreaser + cleaning rags + after weekly ptfe spray lubricant (w40 or similar ) chains trolley 1 trolley 2 trolley 3 trolley 4 trolley 5 trolley 6 trolley 7 trolley 8 trolley 9 observations & corrective actions: • material: aisi 316 stainless steel, peek plastic. o nozzles: flat venturi o flow rate: 10-15 liters per minute o precise angulation (15°-25°) the initially established cleaningn frequency is weekly. however, this periodicity must be considered an initial baseline and is subject to continuous review.", "Checklist MTO PVO IBF Cadena Empuje B.2.2 220925 1943.pdf": "b.2.2. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 • equipment: m.02540 • frequency: weekly • inspector: ________________ • date: //___________________ main checklist table: section item verify/check deterioration frequency ✅ complies ❌ fails observations/measurement b. clean - clean + check 2 load-bearing guide rails weekly tactile check: (must be clean) right upper guide erosions or wear on its surfaces left upper guide right botton guide left botton guide right lower guide left lower guide center cam observations & corrective actions:", "Checklist MTO PVO IBF Cadena Empuje B.2.3 220925 1943.pdf": "b.2.3. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 • equipment: m.02540 • frequency: weekly • inspector: ________________ • date: //___________________ main checklist table: section item verify/check deterioration frequency ✅ complies ❌ fails observations/measurement b. clean - clean + check 3 pulleys and chains weekly tactile check: (must be clean) chains trolley 1-2 erosions or wear on its surfaces trolley 2-3 trolley 3-4 trolley 4-5 trolley 5-6 trolley 6-7 trolley 7-8 trolley 8-9 trolley 9-1 pulleys driving shaft drive shaft half-discs driving shaft replacement protocol: replace driving shaft every 2 chain changes purpose: prevents shaft deformation and reduces wear on subsequent chains bearings replace all 3 bearings with every driving shaft change. driven shaft replacement protocol: replace driven shaft every 4 chain changes criteria: based on: disc surface wear diameter reduction bearings replace both bearings with every driven shaft change observations & corrective actions:", "Checklist MTO PVO IBF Cadena Empuje B.2.4 220925 1943.pdf": "b.2.4. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 • equipment: m.02540 • frequency: weekly • inspector: ________________ • date: //___________________ main checklist table: section item verify/check deterioration frequency ✅ complies ❌ fails observations/measurement b. clean - cleaning + check 4 bearings and trolleys axles weekly tactile check: (must be clean) bearings trolley 1 looseness or oscillations axles trolley 2 movement test: trolley 3 verify parts move freely (bearings, joints). trolley 4 clearance measurement: trolley 5 use feeler gauges to check gaps. trolley 6 trolley 7 trolley 8 trolley 9 observations & corrective actions: check the condition of central and side bearings inthe entry zone (red circle) where more efficient inspection can be perfomed.", "Checklist MTO PVO IBF Cadena Empuje B.2.5 220925 1943.pdf": "b.2.5. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 • equipment: m.02540 • frequency: weekly • inspector: ________________ • date: //_______ main checklist table: section item verify/check deterioration frequency ✅ complies ❌ fails observations/measurement b. clean - clean + check 5 trolleys plaques for tooths weekly tactile check: (must be clean) right plaque trolley 1 deterioration or erosion of the plaques may look for cracks, chips, or deformation. left plaque trolley 1 cause deformation or damage to the mold´s dimensional check: right plaque trolley 2 push base wich can shorten the mold´s measure thickness to detect material loss. left plaque trolley 2 service life. surface check: right plaque trolley 3 feel for roughness or grooves indicating wear. left plaque trolley 3 right plaque trolley 4 left plaque trolley 4 right plaque trolley 5 left plaque trolley 5 right plaque trolley 6 left plaque trolley 6 right plaque trolley 7 left plaque trolley 7 right plaque trolley 8 left plaque trolley 8 right plaque trolley 9 left plaque trolley 9 observations & corrective actions:", "Checklist MTO PVO IBF Cadena Empuje C.2.6 220925 1943.pdf": "c.2.6. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 • equipment: m.02540 • frequency: weekly • inspector: ___________________ • date: //_______ main checklist table: section item manual verification and condition assessment frequency ✅ complies ❌ fails observations/measurement c. check 6 anti -lift device molds weekly tactile check: (must be clean) duroglis look for cracks, chips, or deformation. cylinder ev.cylinder inspect the condition of : sensor deterioration the duroglis guide for adjustment or fc .molds replacement as needed. pressure r. observations & corrective actions: operation of the cylinder position sensor operation of the f.c. position sensor air leaks in : cylinder pneumatic hoses solenoid valve pressure regulator", "Checklist MTO PVO IBF Cadena Empuje D.2.7 220925 1943.pdf": "d.2.7. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 • equipment: m.02540 • frequency: weekly • inspector: ___________________ • date: //_______ main checklist table: section item identification of trolley lubrication points frequency ✅ complies ❌ fails observations/measurement d. lubricating 7 trolleys grease fittings weekly the initially established lubrication frequency is weekly. grease fitting 1 however, this periodicity must be considered an initial baseline and is subject to fitting 2 continuous review. fitting 3 fitting 4 fitting 5 fitting 6 grease must flow smoothly from until clean grease appears (flushes out old/degraded grease). no excess grease should accumulate (wipe off surplus to avoid dust buildup). observations & corrective actions:", "Checklist MTO PVO IBF Cadena Empuje E.2.8 220925 1943.pdf": "e.2.8. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 • equipment: m.02540 • frequency: weekly • inspector: ___________________ • date: //_______ main checklist table: section item identification of molds lubrication points. frequency ✅ complies ❌ fails observations/measurement e. lubrication 8 lubrication system for mold guides weekly the initially established lubrication frequency is weekly. oil nozzle 1 however, this periodicity must be considered an initial baseline and is subject to nozzle 2 continuous review. nozzle 3 nozzle 4 nozzle 5 nozzle 6 lubricate only whenreally necessary and according to the mold conditions. excessive application harms the movement of the molds on the polycords / guides and the bases of angles of the elevators. clean with brushes and cloths on the switchboard, tubes, and nozzles. observations & corrective actions: perform visual inspection for: oil contamination in the ground due to losses in the control unit or in the tubes to the nozzles. central unit filling nozzles / rollers dirt nozzles / rollers dirt", "Checklist MTO PVO IBF Cadena Empuje M.3.1 220925 1943.pdf": "m.3.1. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 • equipment: m.02540 • frequency: monthly • inspector: ___________________ • date: //_______ main checklist table: section item verify/check measurements frequency ✅ complies ❌ fails observations/measurement m. special check - measurements & tracki 1 chain elongation measurement monthly link to register measure with a large analog or digital calliper. trolley 1 trolley 2 to ensure consistency and accuracy in all measurements, always measure the distance between the two trolley 3 trolleys using the same fixed reference point as the origin. \"benchmark\". trolley 4 trolley 5 trolley 6 trolley 7 trolley 8 trolley 9 observations & corrective actions: when chain elongation reaches 424 / 425 mm the chain has reached its end of service life and must be replaced.", "Checklist MTO PVO IBF Cadena Empuje M.3.2 220925 1943.pdf": "m.3.2. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 • equipment: m.02540 • frequency: monthly • inspector: ___________________ • date: //_______ main checklist table: section item verify/check measurements frequency ✅ complies ❌ fails observations/measurement m. special check - measurements & tracki 2 chain tension in tensioning links monthly link to register measure with a large analog or digital calliper. washers sup-f-uct observations & corrective actions: tensioning must be applied equally on both chain tension must be monitored to evaluate sides and the tension should allow proper wear progression.\" operation of the compression washers. if over-tighened ,these washers will not function.", "Checklist MTO PVO IBF Cadena Empuje M.3.3 220925 1943.pdf": "m.3.3. checklist - pallet pushing system tm-101 • equipment: m.02540 • frequency: monthly • inspector: ___________________ • date: //_______ main checklist table: section item verify/check measurements frequency ✅ complies ❌ fails observations/measurement m. special check - measurements & tracking 3 polycord wear (trolleys 1-9) monthly link to register measure with a small analog or digital calliper. policord 1 policord 2 policord 3 policord 4 policord 5 policord 6 observations & corrective actions: the lengths of the polycords must be adjusted adjusted according to the needs of each point. the measurements of the policors are the same in each of the 9 trolleys measure the polycords and adjust them replace any polycord if : to the reference length as required. its length no longer allows proper adjusment it has lost its stiffness.", "Evaluation of Timings and Responsibilities 220925.pdf": "evaluation of timings and responsibilities (220925) 1. daily maintenance (10-15 minutes) - responsible: machine operator o superficial cleaning with an air gun and visual inspection, performed during the downtime at the end of production (integrated into the standard workstation cleaning and tidying routine). 2. weekly maintenance (total duration: 60 minutes) o a production stop of 30-60 minutes is scheduled, typically on a fixed day (e.g., friday afternoon). the alternative is having a dedicated person handle this after production ends. o phase 1 (30 min) - operator: thorough cleaning of the chain and components. this removes heavy debris, allowing the mechanic to work efficiently and safely. o phase 2 (30 min) - mechanic: exhaustive technical inspection (according to a checklist) of alignment, sprocket wear, lubrication, and tension adjustment. the prior work by the operator makes the mechanic's 30 minutes highly productive. 3. monthly / bimonthly maintenance (30 minutes) - responsible: mechanic o measurement checks (chain elongation, clearances) and verification of technical parameters. o based on the results, the frequency can be extended to bimonthly (every 2 months). o this task is performed immediately after the scheduled weekly cleaning, taking advantage of the machine already being stopped and clean. the 30 minutes are added to the weekly stop on that specific day.", "18.RAW MATERIALS - EQUIPMENT & INSTALLATIONS.pdf": "1 raw materials / equipment and installations. sands : mining of sands 2 mining of sands stock area of the supplier with sand to supply us. natural sand: fine natural sand of silicic origin. material free of clays and with a high sand equivalent. (0 to 2 mm) 3 mining of sands natural sand washed: natural sand washed very fine of silicic origin. material free of clays and with a high sand equivalent. (0 to 2 mm) sand washed from river : sand from natural gravel pits. lower content in fines and a high equivalent of sand. this type of aggregate concentrates a greater quantity of quartz and stone of great hardness. (0 to 3mm and 0 to 5mm) 4 mining of sands crushing sand. pit sand: sand from limestone rocks. material free of clays and with a high sand equivalent. (0 to 2 and 0 to 5 mm) gravel eye partridge: sand from the crushing of limestone aggregates. exempt of clays. live singing edges. partridge eye from 3 to 5 mm. 5 granulometry equipment to perform the \"granulometry” precision scale. stove or fire cooking. sifting with different sieves. 6 granulometry. the minerals in the sand no problem feldspar, mica, iron pyrite, iron oxide, pyroxenes / amphiboles the stone fragments unacceptable : calcium, clay, soft irestone / silstone the theoretical ideal sand in my opinion, the possible theoretical ideal sand for the production should be of the following granulometry. nº sieve. size in mm. % % of the total 4 4,76 0 0 8 2,38 10 10 12 1,7 17 7 116 1,19 27 10 30 0,59 57 30 50 0,297 78 21 100 0,149 94 16 200 0,074 97 3 powder 0,05 3 100 an proposal of a theoretical mix of 3 existing sands (gross, fine and crushing) 7 granulometry. prefixed objectives : fineness modul ………( 2,7 to 3% ) fines 1 ……..………….( 2 to 5 % ) sand equivalent …….( 80 to 85 %) fineness modul the calculation is made by adding the retained percentages of the sieves. 4+2+1+0,5+0,25+0,125 and dividing them by 100. fines 1 it is the loss of fines that passes through the sieve of 0.0623 mm with the help of water (it is called fine washing) the percentage of fines lost due to this washing is valued as a percentage 8 granulometry. sand equivalent. the sand equivalent test indicates the ratio between the granular and clay elements of an aggregate ( sand). sand equivalent (ea) = (sand measuring / clay measuring) x 100 there is very little difference between the values sand and the upper part of the clay. 9 granulometry. ideal sand 10 mix of sands. as a reference of sand mixtures we can indicate 2 real mixtures in different factories with different proportions and classes of sands. sand 0/5 605 kg. + 0/5 160 kg. + 0/2 crushing sand 135 kg. = 900 kg. máx = 15% sand 0/4 503 kg. + 0/4 504 kg. + 0/2 271 kg. = 1.278 kg. for each profile and model you will have different amounts of sand in these 2 factories 3,443 kg / unit 3, 448 kg / unit 3,450 kg / unit 3,625 kg / unit there may be dispersions by thickness of the tile or by the mold itself. cement as a reference for cement weights, we can indicate actual cement weighings in different factories with different proportions and possibilities of cement. the cement weights in the mix for a factory that doubles are usually for the first 2 or 3 hours of production start in the morning. normal curing 220 kg. i 42,5r pórtland. short curing 115 kg. i 42,5r pórtland + 115 kg. i 52,5 pórtland normal curing 350 kg./ 380 kg i 42,5r pórtland. short curing 280 / 310 kg i 42,5r pórtland.+ 40 / 70 kg.i 52,5 pórt. the cement weights in the tile are reference to a type of mold and model that can be optimized or not. 0,973 kg / unit 0,943 kg / unit 0,942 kg / unit 0,932 kg / unit 11 depending on the moulds there is a greater or lesser use of cement, as a guideline as a reference: kg / unit 0,877 wave s. 0,913 1,045 additives. chemical products many years ago, we added cement, fly ash, steel slag, by-products, etc. the cement companies were added to their cement recipe. plasticizing do not use chemical products, powders or liquids in the tile mix that can alter the structural characteristics (to achieve a greater initial resistance or a greater plasticity of the mortar) (accelerators, stiffeners, setting retarders, etc.) so far in my experience i have not identified that provide more advantages, on the contrary if i have identified disadvantages in its use. (there may be other criteria in this regard, which i respect but do not share). in factories for surface finishes such as slurry si, small doses are used for the formation of a 1 mm layer and alter its characteristics. waterproofing add elements / components for a contribution of fines (if the sand used did not have enough fines) whose objective was to increase and solve problems of impermeability without other purpose and not to alter the structure of the resulting concrete. i consider it necessary to add a little waterproofing to guarantee waterproofing. i can only contrast the use of calcium stearate and zinc powder has been my experience in this product because we had a supplier and a good price. in additions to the manual mixer were made by volume. with values of 0.822 grams / tile to a maximum (exceptional) of 4 grams. as means 0,894, 1,5, 1,8, 2,7 grams / unit according to factories and profiles. the one that requires more waterproofing by profiles, is the flat tile. the waterproofing tests for the guarantee certificate give the evaluation of the waterproofing addition needs, 12 mixer mixer cycles check and ensure if the cycles of the mixer for the dry and wet mortar are sufficient for a good cycle in the mixer for the good homogenization of the mortar. it is necessary to achieve good homogenization without lumps. there are 2 times, one of discharge of sand, cement, additives and water that depend on the systems of addition and others that depend on the energy that brings the mixer in the dry mix (sand , cement, pigment, additives) that depend on the systems of addition and others that depend on the energy provided by the mixture in the dry mix and the wet mix (sand, cement, pigment, additives + water) all usually mixers have a humidity / moisture meter, 1) the test time for sand humidity 25 \" 2) dry mix 30 \"/ 40\" 3) the wet mix 50 \"/ 70\" total 150 \"/ 170\" 100% mixer capacity at 105 t.p.m x 4.6 kg x 180 \"= 1500 kg of minimum mixture. the mixing time is given by the good homogenization in the mixer is given by the characteristics of the mixer. maximum capacity for 1,400 kgs. 60 tpm. minimum kneading time ...... .. cycle 195 \"(schlosser) for a factory at 60 / 85 tiles per minute. ratio sand / cement the ratio used of sand / cement most used in spain, depending on whether the tile mould is optimized or not . 3,2 to 3,9 ratio the reference in italy ……….....….…. .3,3 13 example recipe mix (sand/cement): fine sand 0/2 ……..360 kgs. gross sand 0/5 ...…740 kgs. cement.....…………300 kgs. with the best mix of sands, cement can be reduced, but it will always indicate it the strength of the tile in the resistance test. fine sand look better, thicker sand improves the resistance. . mixture moisture the factories were started manually, the operator added the water, after with a cuadalimeter to then automatically add a few programmed liters and a final adjustment manualy. at present, the moisture of the concrete is monitored by an automatic sensor system in the mixer. what is the ideal moisture of the mixture in the mixer? the moisture of the ideal mortar that we look for in our conditions are from 8% to 9%. (the objective is generally 8.5%) it can reach up to 10% in very special cases of sand and tile profile, it is good identify the moisture in the mixture. example recipe mixture: sand / cement = 3.66 fine sand 0/2 ... 360 kgs. gross sand 0/5 ... 740 kgs. cement ............ 300 kgs. water ............... 60 to 65 liters. moisture mortar from 8.3% to 9%. mix time………… ...... ..195 \" (depending on the type of mixer) there is a ratio that is used in concrete for building, it is water / cement. 14 pigment always from the beginning of the factory has worked with powder pigment manually. *as a reference for pigment weights, we can indicate actual weighings of pigments in different factories with different proportions and possibilities of pigment for each tile color. in order to match the tile colors of all the factories, we must compensate different color of the sands and cement. examples of pigment percentages and weights in the tile. p / c: grey 3,18 %. p / c: brown 3,64 %. p / c: grey 4,55 % (flat tile by color intensity). p / c: grey 2,8 %. p / c: brown 2,7 %. 27,613 g / unit 25,161 g / unit 18,848 g / unit 17,38 g / unit arganda del rey 090222", "27.Customer batching & mixing evaluation.pdf": "1 report suggestions o advices bristile 2023 (300123 to 030223) dandenong sands *in my evaluation, the optimum sand for the production should be of the following granulometry. nº sieve. size in mm. % % of the total 4 4,76 0 0 8 2,38 10 10 12 1,7 17 7 116 1,19 27 10 30 0,59 57 30 50 0,297 78 21 100 0,149 94 16 200 0,074 97 3 powder 0,05 3 100 *prefixed objectives : fineness modul ( 2,85 )……….( 2,7 a 3 ) fines 1 ( 5%)…………………….( 2 a 5 % ) sand equivalent ( 2,85 )……….( 80 al 85 %) sand weighing hopper *sand weighing hopper,to consider discharges on a discontinuous basis to mixer, to reduce dirt in the mixer. *eliminate crushing sand screws, which are currently not functioning. cement weighing hopper *cement weighing hopper (eliminate pneumatic vibrator hopper by an impact vibrator). *the sand/cement ratio, that i have used it in factories is “3,65 to 4,09” 2 additives waterprofing : *to reduce or avoid impermeability problems in concrete tiles, try addingadd in the mixture “calcium stearate”. plasticizing *do not use chemical products, powders or liquids in the tile mix that can alter the structural characteristics (to achieve a greater initial resistance or a greater plasticity of the mortar) (accelerators, stiffeners, setting retarders, etc.) so far in my experience i have not identified that provide more advantages, on the contrary if i have identified disadvantages in its use. there may be other criteria in this regard, which i respect ,”i do not have experience”. *in factories for surface finishes such as slurry yes,(“summer < +25º” ) small doses are used for the formation of a 1 mm layer and alter its characteristics. water mixer. *hot water for winter by (heat excanger) or alternative water heating system to the mixer, to achieve a minimum temperature of mixture 20 to 25 ºc. *depending on the properties of the water in the settling tanks, the water can be reused in the mixture process. 3 mixer situation. *excessive dirt in all areas of the mixer, too much material left on top/botton of the mixer satellites. cleaner the cleaning mode is manual ,a lot of effort and time (i've only seen dry cleaning?)with pneumatic hammer and other tools. *i consider that the cleaning should be complemented by cleaning with the high pressure pump and the application of the liquid, thereby avoiding the incrustations. zetolan mek 3. 4 “once the inside of the mixer has been cleaned, it is advisable to impregnate this liquid with the exterior of all the elements that may come into contact with the concrete of the mixer, thereby avoiding the incrustations and the ones that are generated can be easily cleaned.” *in order to channel the water generated during the cleaning of the mixer, it would be necessary to make a channel in the floor from the concrete mixer to the settling basins. how to make the mixer less dirty. *a complementary objective is how to reduce the creation of dirt, in the operation of adding sand, cement and pigment. *the sand should be discharged pulsatingly into the mixer, once the sand discharge is finished, the cement should be discharged, i recommend to extend the piping inside the mixer with a rubber sleeve. *is necessary water supply ( some nozzles) to the inside of the mixer, in order to” clean the mixer” as much as posible on the feed so that they are above the satellites mixer. 5 mixer safety *lthough there are safety devices to prevent the mixer from starting instantly, i consider that it would be necessary to install 3 more devices, to prevent it from not being possible to *fit safety locks on the 3 cleaning access covers. moisture mixture *install mositure control system at the base of the mixer, i recommend hidronix vi or similar. 6 hopper mixer excessive dirt, a lot of effort and time *it should not be round, it should be straight like the general factory hopper. *consider installing a longer straight hopper ( measurements are approximate) avoid impacts and retention of concrete in the hopper. *hopper with plastic lining and after cleaning apply “zetolan” antifouling liquid. 7 dust collection filter concrete mixer *a dust collector would have to be installed in the concrete mixer and at other points where necessary. mixer area *the entire working area of the mixer, floors and side enclosures would have to be reconditioned. 8 belt conveyor mixer to central hopper. *possible accommodation of the scraper at the front, in the middle area of the lower part of the traction roller with tensioners. ( if it works well, there is no need to change) overhaul of the belt base rollers. anti-fall system of the 2 lower belt rollers. cover belt lower part of the belt in the passage of persons.(safety) 9 hopper central factory *very closed at the bottom, i think that should be wider with more vertical sides due to the width of the belt. belt hopper central to extruder. the position of the front roller is set back to facilitate the removal of the hopper and extruder head. i i *i think that the belt is possible deflected to the right, possible inspection by the maintenance mechanic.", "3.Sand granulometry.pdf": "prefixed objectives of sand 260821 : fineness modul ( 2,85 )……….( 2,7 a 3 )……….real……..3,07 fines 1 ( 5%)…………………….( 2 a 5 % )............real…….1,97% sand equivalent ( 2,85 )……….( 80 al 85 %)…..real….…85,3 % granulometry. the optimum sand for the production should be of the following granulometry. nº sieve. size in mm. % % of the total 4 4,76 0 0 8 2,38 10 10 12 1,7 17 7 116 1,19 27 10 30 0,59 57 30 50 0,297 78 21 100 0,149 94 16 200 0,074 97 3 powder 0,05 3 100 granulometry. prefixed objectives : fineness modul ( 2,85 )……….( 2,7 a 3 )……….real……..3,07 fines 1 ( 5%)…………………….( 2 a 5 % )............real…….1,97% sand equivalent ( 2,85 )……….( 80 al 85 %)…..real……85,3 % fineness modul the calculation is made by adding the retained percentages of the sieves. 4+2+1+0,5+0,25+0,125 and dividing them by 100. fines 1 it is the loss of fines that passes through the sieve of 0.0623 mm with the help of water (it is called fine washing) the percentage of fines lost due to this washing is valued as a percentage granulometry. sand equivalent. the sand equivalent test indicates the ratio between the granular and clay elements of an aggregate ( sand). sand equivalent (ea) = (sand measuring / clay measuring) x 100 there is very little difference between the values sand and the upper part of the clay. arganda del rey 260821", "36.Raw materials excursus.pdf": "1 onur grup kiremit raw materials may 2023 2 sand the sand is the first material necessary for a good quality concrete roof tile, it is necessary to choose a sand or possible sands to be supplied to the factory but that allows to achieve some initial characteristics on the fines of the sand and that its granulometry, in its mixtures, achieves an \"optimal curve of prefixed granulometry\". most of the factories in their storage hoppers are prepared for a possible mixture of 2 or 3 sands, which is usual in the installations to achieve a good mixture of sand. in reference to the characteristics of the type of sand to be used, it is preferable that the sand be river sand because of the better cohesion achieved in the mixture (sand, pigment cement, water) and the easier extrusion of the concrete tile, with less wear on the components of the extruder (rollers and slippers). it is possible to use crushed sand, in the case of using it is advisable in my experience with a maximum percentage of 15% of the total, a percentage higher than that amount as 60% can be used, but the mixer will require a greater demand / efficiency in the moisture control of the final mixture and ensure a good mixing, in order to achieve a stable moisture content of the mixture to achieve greater fluidity in the extruder, it will also cause a greater/rapid wear of the rollers and slippers, an increase in the electrical consumption of the roller and the pusher chain, due to the greater pressure suffered by the slippers during the extrusion of the tile. the following is an example of a possible real mixture of sands in a factory with the need to use 3 sands due to the initial requirements on the sand fines and the pre-set granulometry. reference values for sand fines: fineness modul ( 2,7 % to 3 % ) fines 1 (2 % to 5 % ) sand equivalent ( 80 % al 85 %) 3 the particle size we are looking to achieve with the mixture, according to experience, is that it is as close as possible to the particle size values in the sand indicated below. nº sieve. size in mm. % acumul % o total 4 4,76 0 0 8 2,38 10 10 12 1,7 17 7 116 1,19 27 10 30 0,59 57 30 50 0,297 78 21 100 0,149 94 16 200 0,074 97 3 powder 0,05 100 3 100 it should be noted that the tile with more fine sand has a better surface appearance and increases the weight, the more coarse sand increases the strength, but worsens the surface appearance of the tile and reduces the weight on the concrete tile, all this with \"the same thickness in all parts of the tile\", by changing its density. regarding the minerals in the sand it is important to ensure that the sand used for the manufacture of the concrete roof tile does not contain high levels of sulphates (cracking and fissuring), chlorides (durability), organic matter (voids and bubbles in the tile) or soluble salts (efflorescence). it may be necessary to use special additives or replace the sand with a more suitable type to ensure the quality and durability of the concrete roof tile. 4 ideal sand covered environment separators interior factory a covered. 5 screen the use of a screen is essential to avoid the entrance of stones in the sand that can take the suppliers in the supplies of sand with the truck or that for some reason they are in the sand storage of the factory. the entrance of a stone greater than the minimum thickness of production in the tile can break the mold and what is worse the roller or sleeper of conformation. it is absolutely necessary if for the manufacturing it is going to use equipment of rollers and sleppers of widia. about the type of screens to use, in each factory they have to find which is the one that meets their efficiency and maintenance requirements from their own experience, in my opinion after years using different types of equipment i have my decision on which is the best screen with guarantees and reduction of maintenance costs, the only and big problem is its initial cost. “ hein, lehmann “ system : liwell https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xlzwfj4qer8 tipe lsf 1,0 2,58/8 ed support legnth: 2.700 mm distance betwen silentblocks: 2.600 mm width betwen silentblocks: 1.200 mm 6 screen 7 cement types of cement supplier the cement normally used is portland according to certifications i 42,5r portland. i 52,5r portland normally concrete tiles are produced with portland 42.5 and/or portland 52.5, depending on the countries (north / south) and the need for more or less curing hours, so that they can have a good demoulding (without breakage) and with sufficient strength and less brittleness to allow good packaging and palletising. according to the characteristics of the cement manufacturer in spain, i 42,5 portland has a setting time of 60 minutes and i 52,5 portland has a setting time of 45 minutes, which means that the hardening time of i 52,5 portland is faster, but with enough time to be able to produce the tile without problems in the extruder head. i 52.5 portland also achieves a higher strength of 50 % in 48 hours compared to i 42.5 portland. the time it takes to reach its final strength or cure is 28 days, the mission of the cement is to react with the sand and the water, to provoke the setting of the resulting material with the help of the curing process of the tiles in their chambers, to obtain a tile with a strength that allows its demoulding (depalletiser) and its transfer by the polycores and its subsequent packaging and palletising. the color cement needs to be monitored if the tile is not painted, since with only powder pigment the colour of the final tile can be lighter or darker” what is the ideal amount of cement for the tile? there is a theoretical approximation of the kilos per mix, but in the end it will be determined by the practical results of the resistance tests in the factory. on the other hand, when there is a double shift and it is posible mixed (i 42,5 portland + i 52,5 portland) with another more reactive cement, the proportions will be determined in the situation of the tiles in the demoulding and packaging. real examples : 1 shift 350 kg. i 42,5 portland 2 shift 380 kg. (280 kilos i 42,5 portland + 70 kg. i52,5 portland) the ratio used of sand / cement spain 3,64. 8 ratio sand / cement the ratio used of sand / cement most used in in the different profiles of the factories i have visited: 3,05 to 4,09 the ratio used of sand / cement spain…. 3,64. the ratio used of sand / cement italy….. 3,30. vaults in cement weighing hoppers it is convenient to replace the pneumatic / electric vibrators with impact vibrators to break the vaults created inside the cement weigh hoppers. 9 pigment powder pigment is a very standardised product, so today there are many suppliers of this synthetic iron oxide. bayer ag, cathay pigments, lanxess, rockwood italia (silo) manual - dosage of powder pigment to the mixer automatic- dosage of powdwer pigment to the mixer 10 always from the beginning of the factory has worked with powder pigment manually. the pigment was supplied in paper bags and more later in big-bag. depending on the accuracy required, the pigment is added manually by volume. the best thing is a table near the mixer and a weighing scale with some cubes to make the recipe. *as a reference for pigment weights, we can indicate actual weighing of pigments in different factories with different proportions and possibilities of pigment for each tile color. (without surface painting) *in order to match the tile colors of all the factories, we must compensate different color of the sands and cement. (without surface painting) p / c : grey 2,8 % to 3,18 % . p / c : brown 2,7 % to 3,64 % . p / c : grey 4,55 % ( flat tile by color intensity). liquid pigment most of the factories in the world use powder pigments, liquid pigments are in the minority, i personally always recommend powder pigments. the installation of the liquid pigment takes up a lot of space and they have to be in constant agitation to avoid decanting. i can improve the dispersion, but i do not like the use of more water because of the pigment. it is possible to realize by means of big-bag of pigment emptying it in a big container and rest water, keeping it always in constant agitation 11 additives. chemical products many years ago, we added cement, fly ash, steel slag, by-products, etc. the cement companies were added to their cement recipe. plasticizing do not use chemical products, powders or liquids in the tile mix that can alter the structural characteristics (to achieve a greater initial resistance or a greater plasticity of the mortar) (accelerators, stiffeners, setting retarders, etc.) so far in my experience i have not identified that provide more advantages, on the contrary if i have identified disadvantages in its use. (there may be other criteria in this regard, which i respect but do not share). in factories for surface finishes such as slurry , small doses are used for the formation of a 1 mm layer and alter its characteristics. waterproofing add elements / components for a contribution of fines (if the sand used did not have enough fines) whose objective was to increase and solve problems of impermeability without other purpose and not to alter the structure of the resulting concrete. i consider it necessary to add a little waterproofing to guarantee waterproofing. i can only contrast the use of calcium stearate and zinc powder has been my experience in this product because we had a supplier and a good price. in additions to the manual mixer were made by volume. with values of 0.822 grams / tile to a maximum (exceptional) of 4 grams. the one that requires more waterproofing by profiles, is the flat tile. the waterproofing tests for the guarantee certificate give the evaluation of the waterproofing addition needs, accelerator additives this additive i do not use, nor have i ever used, and the least recommended for my part, as it does not guarantee the quality properties of the tiles that we demand in the production process in spain, until they personally prove me otherwise in a factory. obtaining a high strength in a concrete tile in a short time has always been an objective for the technicians of all central laboratories. the additive accelerator in the production has not been recommended because it has a great reduction of the setting time that can cause failures in the humidity control sensor of the mixer, difficulties in the shaping of the tile in the extruder box, subsequent problems in the formation of micro-cracks, fissures and cracks in the curing stage in the chambers, the quality defects are very difficult to identify when the tile is painted on its surface. 12 water feeding mixer. natural water / cold feed water to the mixer by well water or the external network recovered water from decantation pond. hot water use hot water in the mixer to get the 20º to 25º temperature of the concrete in the mixer where it is necessary. ( boiler / exchanger) 13 steam water the purpose of adding steam to the mixer is to reach a mixing temperature of 20 to 25º, normally in the winter season, and to break up any grains of frozen sand from the yard or from the roof tiles, in order to achieve a good mix in the mixer, as they could cause a defect on the surface of the tile.", "4.Notes on raw materials.pdf": "notas sobre las materias primas (13/06/2020) components of mix for the production of concrete roof tiles ingredients description sand max. granulometry 3 mm. the sand must be washed and clay free. it is recommended to use river sand rather than quarry sand as it is less abrasive and gives a better surface finish. cement portland 400/425. lower grade cement can be used, but may not set strongly enough in 24 hours. water water without impurities. impurities may affect the setting of the cement. colourant iron or chromium oxides normally found on the mark the most widely used oxide colouring agents, i.e. the agents added to the mix to obtain coloured concrete roof tiles, are in the list above (oxide colouring agents). the quantity of colouring agent to be added to the mix varies from a minimum of 2.5% to a maximum of 4 % of the quantity of cement aridos el árido optimo para la producción como referencia puede ser de la siguiente granulometría. nº tamiz. abertura en mm. % % del total 4 4,76 0 0 8 2,38 10 10 12 1,7 17 7 116 1,19 27 10 30 0,59 57 30 50 0,297 78 21 100 0,149 94 16 200 0,074 97 3 polvo 0,05 3 100 por abajo arena por arriba. nº tamiz. abertura en mm. izda. ideal. dcha. 4 4,76 0 0 0 0 0 8 2,38 17 17 10 5 5 12 1,7 27 10 7 4 9 116 1,19 37 10 10 8 17 30 0,59 65 28 30 32 49 50 0,297 83 18 21 24 73 100 0,149 97 14 16 19 92 200 0,074 99 2 3 3 95 polvo 0,05 3 cemento. i 42,5r pórtland.( 100%) los pesos de cemento en la teja, son de referencia para un tipo de molde y modelo que puede ser optimizado o no, en el caso de españa el ratio de arena/cemento utilizado en nuestras tejas son del 3,42 al 4,09(teja plana) en italia trabajan con el………….... 3,3 con la mejor mezcla de áridos se puede reducir el cemento, pero siempre lo indicará la resistencia de la teja al desmoldeo y el empaquetado/paletizado. arena fina mejor aspecto, mayor arena gruesa mejora la resistencia. pigmento con el fin de igualar los colores de teja de todas las fábricas, debiendo compensar diferente color de las arenas y el cemento. p / c : marron 2,7 % . p / c : rojo 2,71 % . p / c : gris 2,8 % . p / c : gris 3,18 % . p / c : marron 3,64 % . p / c : gris 4,55 % ( t. plana por intensidad color). impermeabilizantes / hidrofugos el objetivo del impermeabilizante es adicionar elementos / componentes para una aportación de finos ( si la arena utilizada no tuviera suficientes finos ) cuyo objetivo fuera aumentar y resolver problemas de impermeabilidad sin otra finalidad y no alterar la estructura del hormigón resultante. es necesario añadir un poco de impermeabilizante para garantizar la impermeabilidad, se han utilizado habitualmente estearatos en polvo. 0,822 gramos / teja hasta 3 gramos, en función del tipo de arena.. las pruebas de impermeabilidad están establecidas para el certificado de garantía. humedad del hormigón la humedad de la pasta ideal que buscamos en nuestras condiciones son del 8 % al 9 %. el objetivo generalmente es el 8,5 % puede llegar hasta el 10 % en casos muy especiales de árido y perfil teja, es bueno identificar la humedad de la pasta. =======================================================", "6.Suggestions on Concrete Mix.pdf": "1 riccardo campigotto da: miguel blanes <blanes.miguel@gmail.com> inviato: lunedì 19 luglio 2021 11:37 a: roberto berti cc: riccardo campigotto oggetto: re: i: ackerstein's roof tiles hi roberto, in relation to the differences that i identify in the tiles in the photos, i consider that there may be several possibilities or some that are the sum of them that can give this result, i do not indicate anything about the extrusion conditions “extrusión head” , without first knowing the basis of the raw materials and their mixture in the concrete mixer: 1) the granulometry of the sand, normally it is indicated from 0 to 5 mm, but the percentage of sand grains of 4.76 mm is almost 0 %, (since in the areas of the minimum thickness of the tile that grain size is of no interest) so from 3/ 3.5 mm is the largest working grain and with a maximum percentage of 15%. (it would be necessary to know the granulometric curve of the sand to evaluate). 2) the type of sand is another important part, if the origin of the sand is from the river and with rounded faces it is the best, it can be from a mine, on the other hand, crushed sand is the worst to work with. (it would be necessary to find out where the sand used comes from) 3) the good mixture in the concrete mixer, the mixture times in dry and wet must be the best to mix the materials well, so that there is a good cohesion of all the raw materials. (it is necessary to know the raw materials used and the mixture times for each of them) 4) excess water can cause voids in the concrete during extrusion, which can be identified in the cut. (the working moisture of the concrete should be known) i remain open to any questions or comments. thank you. best regards.", "23.EXTRUSION HEAD SETTINGS.pdf": "1 extrusion head / roof tile forming the tile shapping process that i am going to present consists of 16 indicators that i consider \"necessary to take into account\", in order to control the whole \"tile shaping process\". in the development of this process, each factory can expand or reduce the proposed indicators as they see fit. there are 4 main indicators in this process, which are the measures of adjustment of the tile head, a, b, c and d, they are very particular for each model of tile and conditioned to the raw materials that are used for the manufacture of the tile. the measurements \"a\", \"b\", \"c\" and \"d\" correspond to: \"a\" = distance from the bench guides to the flat areas of the roller, according to the thickness of the tile in the flat area minus the height of the mould. \"b\" = distance from the bench guides to the big slipper entrance. \"c\" = distance from the bench guides to the exit of the big slipper. (\"track slipper inclination mm\" = b - c) \"d\" = distance from the big slipper to the big roller \"gap d\". 2 initially for measures b, c and d, there are reference values, as detailed in the table below, always depending on the type of sand (fine / coarse) used. there is also an initial reference roller speed, the calculation values are the speed (tiles/minute) and the smallest roller diameter of the tile profile. however, once in production with the other settings, it can vary, any excess of the roller speed will result in increased wear of the roller so far, 6 indicators of the process have been presented. to understand a little more about the shaping of the tile on a mould, the philosophy is to overfeed concrete into the space between the mould and the roller / slipper, to maintain a fresh concrete on the pallet at a certain compaction, so that it does not deform during the whole process of cutting, moving and stacking. 1 r.p.m. 2 r.p.m. 3 mm 4 mm 5 mm 6 mm 7 mm 8 mm 9 mm 10 mm 11 ºc 12 ºc 13 ampere 14 ampere 15 mm 16 t.p.m distance from the big slipper to the big roller.gap(d) column height. tiles per minute roller ammeter pushing chain ammeter maximum roller temperature maximum slipper temperature used roller diameter. height distance between big and small slippers limiters length . ( steel / policord)) new roller diameter. slipper entry height (b) tiles per minute slipper exit height.(c) are established for roller height. (a) production speed of notes steel head or tungsten, double roman roller speed. all these values stirrer speed.( units / dimensions) factory: seccion : automatic extruder e4s 120 tpm process : extrusion head / tile conformation profile nº parameters nominal value minimum value maximum value units process sheet code date: 2022 review number: 1 page: 1 3 all the concrete from the hopper supported on the base of the pallet, is fed by the mould itself towards the roller assisted by the rotation of the roller, in that direction with an initial leakage of concrete between the roller and slipper. at this point there are already more process indicators, which intervene for this shaping, the height of the mixture column in the hopper (mm), the speed of the roller (rpm), units / dimensions of the stirrers and their speed (rpm), mixture limiters in the flat areas of the tile (yes / no) (length mm). 4 5 limiters 6 stirrers the stirrer pins are responsible for feeding concrete in all areas of the tile when the gravity of the concrete column of the hopper, the surface of the aluminum pallet and the rotation of the rollers drag the concrete under the slippers, usually its greater the need is in the less thickness areas of the concrete tile. stirrer pins shaft profiles “venetian” profile singularities in the 2 factories for this profile: it is the stirrer pins shaft with the highest profile and the most demanding need for concrete. 10 units. 12 mm. star pins diameters. at 60º among them. partial sum of the distances in all the holes gives 328 mm, which we only leave 1 mm on each side of the plates, since it corresponds to 330 mm 7 tpm high speed extruder head, “venetian” tile profile with 10 in-line star pins. stirrer pins with diameter 8 mm, widia tablets welded, shaft coated tungsten carbide to prevent wear.. in this extrusion head with a different philosophy, much feed for input by star pins. vertical limiters “arcadia” profile 8 singularities in the 3 factories for this profile: it is the stirrer pins shaft with a smaller profile than the “venetian”, with the wider planes and less need for power. 9 units. 12 mm. stirrer pins diameters. at 60º among them. partial sum of the distances in all the holes gives 327 mm, which we only leave 1.5 mm on each side of the plates, since it corresponds to 330 mm. tpm high speed extrusion head, “arcadia” tile profile with 9 in-line stirrer pins. stirrer pins with diameter 12 mm, widia tablets. in this extrusion head with a different philosophy, much feed for input by stirrer pins. vertical limiters 9 summary: in the examples raised on stirrer pins there is a quantity, distribution and angles between them (90º or 60º) for each profile depending on the needs that may have on the concrete feed, as well as the different diameters and lengths of the removers according to needs. the 2 most critical areas where sometimes more power is required are the underlap water course or the overlap, depending on the profile of those areas. the distributions of the stirrer pins determine an adjustment in the side walls, which ensure that there is no retention of concrete in those walls, remaining always clean. there is nothing a priori that guarantees the feeding of concrete by the stirrer pins to the pallet, what there is an experience as a base of departure, that allows to propose a good development of work, to find (with the practice in the extrusion head) the best type of stirrer pins shaft for that factory based on its raw materials.", "28.Extruder machine evaluations.pdf": "11 designer extruder head. *\"in order to ensure the best possible tile conformation by roller and the slipper, it´s necessary coating the stirrers with tungsten guides. *adjust the upper side guide in underlap wáter course overlap, to be 0.5 mm, to avoid leverage. adjustment of (a) roller heights, end slipper(c) and inclination (b-c). setting 020223 12 artisan, classic y lodge extruder head. *use the same approach as the design head, if necessary. possible causes of breakage roller and slipper big. *one of the possible causes of these breakages on the overlap side of the slipper and roller big is the excess slack in the side locking guide, which allows the guide to be pressed laterally at the bottom, putting excess pressure on the critical areas of the roller and slipper. *i believe that this excess clearance and pressure should be identified and, if necessary, the guide should be pressed on a higher line, outside the critical areas of breakage of roller and slipper big. 13 realise agent applicator *the current system pollutes a “lot”, by the pneumatic pump and nozzles in its application. 14 *better “to change the oil application system” to the new oil curtain application system. *fit anti-fall oil reservoirs ,release agent in application system. moisture control. *a moisture analyser should be available ,in the extruder area for the extruder operator to test the moisture content of the mixture. identify the pallet rise point at the extruder outlet. *point where the pallet is raised and lowered at the extruder outlet. 15 *the pallet retention system at the bottom lateral does not work, the pallet has excessive wear and deformation on the pallet sides, which makes it impossible to clamp the pallet. *lack of pressure or excess wear on the side of the pallet (-2 / 3 mm) or wear on the base (0,5 / 0,7 mm), the free pallet and the pressure exerted by the big slipper between two pallets causes the pallet to rise. (the pallets are a lot wear) 16 push chain system pallets *i don't know this system of “top” thrust pallets, in spain we changed it many years ago, the bottom pallet pusher system is better tile cutting system. *current contamination of the cutter must be avoided in order to keep the cutter in good working order and to reduce maintenance costs. *cover the back of the cutter (metraquilato or other material) to prevent dirt from entering. 17 *place a separation wall between the applicación de slurry and the cutting system tiles,it´s necessary in order not to damage the new cutting system. *concrete debris generated by the tile cutting system and water from the cleaning of the blades, must be collected in a lower box, channelling the water. to prevent it from falling to the floor. 18 dirt on the sides of the pallets *there is dirt on the sides of the pallets, currently in the scraper area, there is a “non-contact área”. *consider placing pallet side scrapers at conveyor feeding pallets to the pusher chain or the exit of the cutting system.( a check and evaluatio of the pallets is necessary) *the pallets with the most lateral dirt are the designer and the artisan. stock pallets 020223 : designer 26.000 pallets artisan 14.000 pallets. classic 24.000 pallets lodge 8.000 pallets. 19 designer mould wear *in addition to the lower wear of the designer pallet, on the side of the underlap wáter course, there is a wear of 2.5 / 3 mm on the support guide, which has led to a deformation of the pallet on that side. *in addition to the lower wear of the designer mould, on the side of the underlap wáter course. .( a check the dimensions of the pallets on a monthly basis, in order to identify possible wear, as early as possible.) *the useful life of a pallete, is considered to be more or less 2,000 passes of the pallet through the extruder head.", "29.Ridge tile extruder settings.pdf": "1 developement ridge tiles wacol 070223 before considering possible improvement developments on the line with the baffle in place, the cleanliness of the sides of the moulds must first be ensured/guaranteed. 2 3 4 test with the same pin stirrer, but think about a possible change in the distribution of the type of stirrer pin. depending on the concrete feed obtained on the pallet. 5 6 setting roller and slipper possible : check the current settings ridge tile and carry out the tests with these settings, then, depending on the pressure, adjust to the possible values. it is very important that the sides of the pallet are “very clean”. as reference , setting ridge tile in spain :", "41.How to synchronize the phase point of the tile cutting Golob 171125.pdf": "1 how to synchronize the phase point of the tile cutting.171125 a) place the cutting system at the central point of its displacement. b) place a mould by positioning with the pushing chain in “ the central area” (its cutting position), cutting blades perpendicular to the bedplate. 2 c) place the cam of the cutting carriage at the upper point x , adjust the arm of the cam for that distance with the cutting carriage. 3 d) . place and close the chain e) adjust the detector cam for the best possible tile cut", "42.ADJUSTING THE GUIDES PUSHING CHAIN AND EXTRUDER BOX 201125.pdf": "1 adjusting the guides: pushing chain and extruder box (201125) 2. checks and verification methodology a) verification of guide dimensions and adjustments  required instruments:  400 mm caliper.  inside caliper to access and take measurements in spaces where the large caliper cannot be positioned correctly.  procedure: measure the width and position of the guides at four critical points: inlet and outlet of the “push chain”, and inlet and outlet of the extrusion box. this will confirm whether the dimensions are correct and uniform (all measurements are with the mold's sides clean).   pushing chain bench box extruder bench 2 fixed bench b) alignment check between guides required instrument:  2000 mm leveling ruler or straight edge.  procedure: place the ruler longitudinally on the push chain guides and extend it towards the guides of the extrusion box (with the latter open). this will allow for visual and physical verification of the continuity and perfect alignment between both sets of guides, identifying any unevenness or lateral displacement. 3 3. ideal adjustment and setup the goal of the adjustment is to achieve a continuous guide system and a perfectly centered push. a) general alignment: all guides (push chain, extrusion box, and cutting carriage) must form a perfectly aligned continuous line. 4 b) centering of the push fingers: the fingers of the trolleys must make contact at the theoretical center point of the mould. the reference dimensions for this centering are: * distance from left finger to left guide: 99.5 mm. * distance from right finger to right guide: 66 mm. c) lateral clearance on the mould: once the fingers are centered, the theoretical clearances between the mould and the fingers must be respected: * left side clearance: 7.5 mm. * right side clearance: 10.5 mm. 5 4. static position and clearance verification of push fingers objective: to verify the geometric position and clearances (lateral and upper) of the push fingers in relation to the mould when the system is in its stable working point. preparation:  1 test mould, modified with an inspection window on its upper section. procedure: 1. place the windowed mould on the push chain. 2. advance the chain until critically positioning the mold: the roller / bearing of the central trolley must be fully supported on the straight and horizontal section of the central guide. this position constitutes the reference where pushing is stable and measurements are valid. 6 parameters to verify: once correctly positioned, measure through the inspection window:  lateral clearances: space between the flanks of the fingers and the internal walls of the mould.  upper clearance: distance between the upper face of the fingers and the mould.  alignment: visual verification of the contact point relative to the designated theoretical position. 5. dynamic verification of push sequence objective: to analyze the sequential behavior and force transition between push fingers of multiple trolleys (3 or 4) during the operational cycle. preparation:  3-4 test moulds, unsuitable for production, modified with upper inspection windows. procedure: 7 1. arrange the windowed moulds consecutively at the start of the chain. 2. pass the set of moulds through simultaneously. 3. visually observe, through the windows, the finger interaction in different cycle phases: o finger under full load: exerting the main push on the lower area of the mould. o finger in disengagement phase: about to lose contact with the mold it's releasing. o finger in pre-push phase: preparing to initiate contact once the forward finger releases its pressure. general conclusion: the correct system alignment fundamentally depends on the precise positioning of the push chain guides relative to their fingers. the static geometric verification (point 4) constitutes the first and most critical step, establishing the reference working condition. once confirmed, this serves as the basis for adjusting the lateral guides of the extrusion box, thereby ensuring integral alignment and operational continuity of the entire line. the dynamic verification (point 5) complements this analysis by validating the correct force transfer during continuous operation. recommendation: document findings from both verifications with photographs or sketches of the inspection windows to generate a technical record of the configuration.", "42.Mould MISALIGNMENT in the  estrusion box 191125.pdf": "1 analysis and solution for mould misalignment in the extrusion box 181125 objective: to identify the root cause and establish the verification and adjustment method to correct the lateral forcing of the moulds against the guides of the extrusion box. 1. theoretical assessment of possible causes following the initial evaluation, the following hypotheses are proposed as the most probable explanations for the lateral deviation of the moulds: 1) hypothesis a: misalignment at the push point. the fingers of the push chain trolleys may not be applying force to the center of the mould, but instead pushing it asymmetrically to one side from the start of the cycle. 2) hypothesis b: general guide misalignment. the guides of the push chain and those of the extrusion box are not on the same plane, creating a progressive deviation at the transition between both sections. 2 3) hypothesis c: displacement of the push chain guides. the push chain guides themselves may be off-center relative to the theoretical axis of the chain, which would generate an incorrect push before the moulds enters the extruder. 2. checks and verification methodology to verify the hypotheses, the following practical checks must be performed: a) verification of guide dimensions and adjustments  required instruments:  400 mm caliper.  inside caliper to access and take measurements in spaces where the large caliper cannot be positioned correctly. 3  procedure: measure the width and position of the guides at four critical points: inlet and outlet of the push chain, and inlet and outlet of the extrusion box. this will confirm whether the dimensions are correct and uniform. b) alignment check between guides required instrument:  2000 mm leveling ruler or straight edge.  procedure: place the ruler longitudinally on the push chain guides and extend it towards the guides of the extrusion box (with the latter open). this will allow for visual and physical verification of the continuity and perfect alignment between both sets of guides, identifying any unevenness or lateral displacement. 4 3. ideal adjustment and setup the goal of the adjustment is to achieve a continuous guide system and a perfectly centered push. 1)general alignment: all guides (push chain, extrusion box, and cutting carriage) must form a perfectly aligned continuous line. 5 2)centering of the push fingers: the fingers of the trolleys must make contact at the theoretical center point of the mould. the reference dimensions for this centering are: * distance from left finger to left guide: 99.5 mm. * distance from right finger to right guide: 66 mm. 3)lateral clearance on the mould: once the fingers are centered, the theoretical clearances between the mould and the fingers must be respected: * left side clearance: 7.5 mm. * right side clearance: 10.5 mm. 6 4. static position and clearance verification of push fingers objective: to verify the geometric position and clearances (lateral and upper) of the push fingers in relation to the mould when the system is in its stable working point. preparation:  1 test mould, modified with an inspection window on its upper section. procedure: 1. place the windowed mould on the push chain. 2. advance the chain until critically positioning the mold: the roller / bearing of the central trolley must be fully supported on the straight and horizontal section of the central guide. this position constitutes the reference where pushing is stable and measurements are valid. 7 parameters to verify: once correctly positioned, measure through the inspection window:  lateral clearances: space between the flanks of the fingers and the internal walls of the mould.  upper clearance: distance between the upper face of the fingers and the mould.  alignment: visual verification of the contact point relative to the designated theoretical position. 5. dynamic verification of push sequence objective: to analyze the sequential behavior and force transition between push fingers of multiple trolleys (3 or 4) during the operational cycle. preparation:  3-4 test moulds, unsuitable for production, modified with upper inspection windows. procedure: 8 1. arrange the windowed moulds consecutively at the start of the chain. 2. pass the set of moulds through simultaneously. 3. visually observe, through the windows, the finger interaction in different cycle phases: o finger under full load: exerting the main push on the lower area of the mould. o finger in disengagement phase: about to lose contact with the mold it's releasing. o finger in pre-push phase: preparing to initiate contact once the forward finger releases its pressure. general conclusion: the correct system alignment fundamentally depends on the precise positioning of the push chain guides relative to their fingers. the static geometric verification (point 4) constitutes the first and most critical step, establishing the reference working condition. once confirmed, this serves as the basis for adjusting the lateral guides of the extrusion box, thereby ensuring integral alignment and operational continuity of the entire line. the dynamic verification (point 5) complements this analysis by validating the correct force transfer during continuous operation. recommendation: document findings from both verifications with photographs or sketches of the inspection windows to generate a technical record of the configuration.", "7.Comments on rake machine.pdf": "notas a comentar para bmi brass rusia 3 231120 por lo que yo puedo entender en los power point e emails. se puede afirmar sin dudas ,que su problema, no es un problema generalizado en este tipo de máquinas de vortex ya que puede ser un problema puntual. indicación de las maquinas implantadas en todo el mundo??? hay que mostrar que no somos los culpables o que no sabe hacer máquinas... todo lo cuestionado: perfiles diferentes rodillos zapatas, distancia ejes removedor al conjunto zapata.. con todo ello, ahora hay justificar lo que ocurre y plantear una posible solución. esa solución de distribuir el hormigón provocan otros problemas de alimentación. hay nivel primero creo que había que solicitar esa información, para entender mejor sus datos y problemas indicados. una vez se disponga de esta información, se les podrá indicar algunas sugerencias y pruebas a realizar para intentar solucionar los problemas que le ocurren. a mi me falta tener más claro la foto mental de la maquina si está disponible en vortex el : i. plano de la bancada de la maquina. ii. plano del molde iii. plano del rodillo iv. plano de la zapata b) ya se ha justificado el porqué, la diferencia del perfil del rodillo respecto a la zapata. it is intentitonial slipper and roller not to have same profile. roller on the two lateral edges allows some material to be “released in between roller and slipper so to reduce pressure and stress on laterla wings of the pallets. en la mayoría de los fabricantes que utilizan está maquina, salvo excepciones por el tipo de materias primas o condiciones muy particulares , el hormigón puede fluir peor en esa zona y surgir problemas de alimentación y compactación. ¿los problemas de alimentación son repetitivos cómo los de la foto, son constantes al 100%?. ¿la humedad del hormigón afecta en algo en a falta de alimentación? ¿los problemas de alimentación han empezado ahora? ( por buscar el origen u otras posibles causas). c) the calibers as probe for this type of tool para identificar mejor los valores que nos indican, sería necesario conocer : ¿como miden estas medidas de rodillo y zapata que se facilitan ? (tienen algún soporte especial ) ¿pueden confirmar si corresponden a a, b y c ? ¿ cual es el gap d.(rodillo y zapata parte superior central)? confirmar si sus datos facilitados corresponden al dibujo siguiente : roller / slipper input - 6.0 a / b slipper in / slipper out - 1.0 ( inclinación 1 mm b / c ) d) confirmar si corresponden las 2 fotos en la misma disposición.? e) facilitar plano o boceto de la disposición actual con las cantidades y longitudes de los removedores(estirrers pin). f) facilitar fotos en general sobre la caja extrusora ( no identifico en las fotos ,todos los componentes, rodillo, zapata, salida de la zapata) desde arriba y los laterales del rodillo y zapata extrusora limpia ( sin tolva), antes de poner la tolva, “additional partition” y después con la tolva limpia y posteriormente cuando haya fabricado. ( para plantear alguna actuación posterior) datos de fabricación actuales : g) altura actual de trabajo de hormigón en la tolva de la extrusora. h) humedad media de trabajo del hormigón? i) velocidad actual de la maquina tpm.( es maquina continua o intermitente) j) velocidades de giro del rodillo y los removedores. k) espesores de trabajo actuales en la parte central , laterales y espesor de los wings. molde. l) pesos de la cumbrera ? =============================================================================", "8.System to adjust roller and slipper.pdf": "", "11.Extruder operators-maintenance people.pdf": "mechanic/electrician all the maintenance operations assigned by the maintenance shift supervisor shall be performed in accordance with the safety regulations set out and with the suitable protective equipment for this job. the actions shall be carried out with the highest degree of professionalism and be assessed to prevent them from happening again, with the purpose of suggesting new actions and reaching a greater efficiency of the machinery. responsibilities - implement the preventive and corrective maintenance tasks in order to reach the highest possible efficiency of the machinery, reducing the production line downtime. - meet the safety regulations set out in each maintenance action. functions - solve the mechanical / electric issues, when required, which might stop the proper functioning of the production line, trying to fix it as soon as possible (also considering the complete repair in maintenance after production). - perform maintenance tasks (inspection routes, lubrication, scheduled repairs and repairs in the production line) according to the indications given by the maintenance/production shift supervisor. - report any anomalies in the machinery and equipment to their maintenance/production shift supervisor. - make regulations specialized in the machinery and equipment. - fill in the daily maintenance sheet. - cooperate in the proper supply of spare parts in the stockyard. - suggest improvements and innovations to increase the efficiency, the quality and the productivity. protective equipment - safety gloves. - safety boots. - noise-abatement ear plugs or headset. 1 extruder mechanic all the maintenance operations indicated by their supervisor shall be performed, meeting the safety regulations set out and using the proper protection means suitable for such work. the actions shall be carried out with the highest degree of professionalism and be assessed to propose actions to prevent them from happening again, with the purpose of a greater efficiency of the machinery. the specialized mechanic in the extruder machine shall supervise the state of this machine with a thorough daily control of all its elements: daily adjustments and wear of all the parts, the wear of rollers and slippers, bench guides, pushing chains and the tile cutting system. responsibilities - undertake the preventive and corrective maintenance tasks with the purpose of a greater efficiency, reducing downtime in the production line. - keep the daily maintenance tasks in the extruder machine in order to reach the tile production quality set out, meeting the concrete roof tile regulations in the (……………… bureau of standards.) - meet the safety regulations set out in each maintenance action / operation. functions - adjustments and control of the extruder machine, the daily wear of all the parts in the machine, the evolution and wear of rollers and slippers, bench guides, pushing chain guides, the pushing chain, chain tensioners, sprockets, trolleys, pushing fingers and the cutting system (blades, guides, rolling bearing and blade cleaning nozzles). - solve the problems which stop the proper functioning of the line. - report any anomalies in the machinery to their maintenance shift supervisor. - fill out the extruder machine maintenance sheet and the daily sheet. - cooperate in the proper supply of the spare parts in the warehouse. - suggest suitable improvements and innovations in order to keep and increase the level of quality and productivity. 2 protective equipment - safety gloves. - safety boots. - noise-abatement ear plugs or headset. or similar. 1 extruder operator these are the instructions to ensure the proper tile formation which fulfils the quality requirements set out. responsibilities - ensure the proper tile formation. - supervise the surface appearance, the cutting and the punching. - control the release agent application. description before production. - review the mould inverter. - check the filling level of the release agent application tank. - check the proper functioning of the oil application. - check the side scrapers on both sides of moulds. - check that the head on the extruder is suitable for the production set out. - check that the tile cutting blades are properly adjusted to the mould profile and to the fixing hole nails. - check the proper functioning of the lubrication application on the base of the mould profiles. - put the extruder head hopper, oil the hopper and all the parts of the machine with a brush and release agent. - oil the moulds which may remain from the oil application to the extruder. - prepare the proper mould supply in the input conveyor to the extruder in order to start. - report any problem or need to the shift supervisor. - if everything is fine, the extruder is ready. at the beginning of production. - fill up the extruder head hopper with concrete. once the above operations have been performed, press the start button in the automatic production line checking that: - the moisture of the mixture is suitable for the formation of the whole tile (through the tile surface appearance and the texture we can determine whether it is properly formed). - the release agent application is correct: when the concrete can be easily separated from the mould without any accumulation of release agent in the mould supporting ribs: 2 o for which it is required to remove one or two moulds at the beginning, in order to validate the release agent application. - the weight of wet tiles is correct in accordance with the tolerances set out. o for which it is required to remove one tile from the production line checking the weight of the tile. if in accordance with the tolerances set out, production shall go on. (if the weight of the tile is out of the tolerances, production shall be stopped and the incident shall be reported to the shift supervisor so as to correct it). the concrete removed from the tile in this operation shall be put into the container for this purpose. - the dimensions and the wet tile punching are correct when in accordance with the tolerances set out: o for which it is required to remove one tile from the production line to check all the dimensions. if in accordance with the tolerances set out, production shall go on. (if any dimensions are out of the tolerances, production shall be stopped and the incident shall be reported to the shift supervisor so as to correct it). the concrete removed from the tile in the operation shall be put into the container for this purpose. ** all the moulds removed from the production line shall be returned to the production line or replaced by others so as not to decrease the number of moulds in the circuit. during production. tile. - check the supply, compaction, release agent application, weights and dimensions of the tiles (one tile per hour). - supervise the effort of the pushing chain and the compaction in the tiles. production line. - supervise the proper functioning of the machinery. - stop the production line in order to correct incidents when: o the cut is wrong. o lack of supply or compaction in tiles. o the concrete moisture is wrong. o the pushing chain works incorrectly. 3 o any anomalies in the functioning of the machines. (being noted in the extruder control sheet.) - ring the bell to alert the mixer operator of any incidents in that area, in the production line or any help needed. - help maintenance in the head change. ** in the event of stops in the production line, assistance must be provided in order to solve the stop as soon as possible. if assistance is not needed, clean the assigned work area. the moisture of the mix. - stay in constant contact with the mixer operator, in case it is required to vary the moisture of the mix (wrong moisture) or to adjust the moisture if a remote adjusting device from the extruder is provided. mould. - remove the moulds stacked in the production line on their way to the extruder or tiles / pieces of tiles which have remained on the mould in the demolding machine. (if it is not removed, it shall stop the production line.) - review all the upper and lower side parts of a mould (at least one mould a day) in order to detect any dirt, erosion, mark or wear and note it in the extruder control sheet. after production. - put the extruder area in manual mode. - empty the extruder head hopper. - clean the work area carrying out the following operations: o unplug the control panel and press the emergency stop button or safety equipment to ensure safe work. o extract the extruder head, lay it on the transportation trolley and clean the entire extruder. o clean the extruder unit according to the cleaning sheet. o clean the assigned work area. - fill out the extruder control sheet and the stop/incident sheet for preventive maintenance. 4 means and work tools - weighing and measurement tables. - tile weighing scale. - calipers to measure thickness, splints and calibration. - small digital depth gauge. - digital caliper of 150 mm or 200 mm. - rectangular calibrated splint of 200x30x6 mm. - round calibrated splint of 200x10 mm diameter. - air compressed feed line. - low flow air gun. protective equipment - safety gloves. - safety boots. - noise-abatement ear plugs or headset. - safety glasses for cleaning and washing the extruder head, the pushing unit and the cutting unit. 5 necessary training before performing this job, the operator must be trained to: - identify the usual wet tile colors and assess the concrete plasticity to make tiles. - identify and use the measurement tools to check the dimensions of tiles. - identify the fixing and adjusting elements of the extruder head. - use all the manual and automatic control panels of the extruder area. in any case, before taking this position, they shall spend at least one week along with another operator who has performed the job satisfactorily for 6 months according to the shift supervisor.", "15.TOOLS USED FOR MEASUREMENTS & TESTING.pdf": "tools used for testing & measurements: the following measuring tools are used for all measuring checks on the fresh and cured tiles during the production process and the quality control of the concrete tiles. a) to measure: fresh and cured tiles thicknesses. 1 small digital caliber 150 mm 1 small digital depth caliber 150 mm b) to measure: big and small rollers & slippers heights and identify the inclinations of the slippers to extrusion head 1 digital comparator c) to measure: tiles (lengths and widths), rollers and slippers (diameters, lengths and widths) 1 digital caliber 500 mm d) to measure: dry tiles thicknesses. 1 small digital micrometer", "20.INTERLOCK SLURRY CLEANER.pdf": "interlock slurry cleaner: the only thing that is needed is that the (mould + tile + slurry) after the application of the slurry, does not move laterally since the brush that cleans it is fixed and it is necessary to control the addition of the dripping on the brush, since the excess of water in the interlock is not good. the dry weight of slurry/tile should be around 120 grams.", "21.CHECKING PRODUCTION DATA.pdf": "checking production data: mixture processsheet extruder process sheet", "22.PROBLEMAS DE MICROFISURAS EN MOLDES NUEVOS.pdf": "problemas de microfisuras en moldes nuevos: indicaciones al respecto: un molde nuevo tiene riesgo en las primeras producciones por el proceso de curado de la teja (fraguado), la generación de micro fisuras en la teja, eso se debe por qué en diferentes zonas del molde , no hay la mínima capa de adherencia a la superficie del aluminio del molde que se crea después de algunas producciones. hasta la fecha en mi experiencia, después de la gran cantidad de moldes nuevos que he puesto en funcionamiento, en diferentes fábricas y con diferentes perfiles de teja, no he logrado que ninguna “aplicación superior en los moldes nuevos” que he aplicado, evite que no puedan salir micro fisuras en los moldes nuevos. ante lo cual , yo recomiendo adoptar la siguiente puesta en funcionamiento de los moldes : 1) cargar los moldes vacíos en las estanterías o carros y aplicarles el calor de las cámaras o túneles habituales, para conseguir que el molde tenga las primeras contracciones y dilataciones ante un ciclo de calor en un ciclo de curado. 2) al día siguiente, aplicar mucho más aceite desmoldeante (+/- 30 % / 40 % ) en la primera producción de tejas ( a valorar en la fabricación ) y seguir bajando esa aplicación hasta la aplicación habitual en las 3 siguientes producciones . 3) todas las tejas producidas en esas 4 producciones deben ser apartadas en el patio para ser revisadas teja a teja para garantizar que no tengan problemas en el tejado, ya que las microfisuras no se pueden detectar en línea habitual de selección.", "26.Slurry application procedures.pdf": "1 report suggestions o advices bristile 2023 (300123 to 030223) dandenong slurry preparation and applicator * a reference dosage in the slurry, depending on the sand used, could be as follows. 2 slurry preparation *the preparation of slurry, which takes place inside the factory in front of the slurry applicator, is actually a source of dirt and contamination in its cutting system and extruder head environment. 3 slurry applicator *the slurry application consists of 2 applicators, with the main applicator running 92 % of the production, the second applicator only running 5 % of the total production. *it has a 260mm belt with a central lower rib, which picks up the tile in the cutter and takes it to the racker. *it generates a lot of slurry residue, accumulated in the 2 lower containers, when applying the slurry to the whole band between the tiles and when there is no tile underneath. 4 *in my opinion the slurry preparation should go next to the concrete mixer, which is the point where the machinery that generates most pollution and dirt should be \"concentrated\". *that is why in the future it could be considered to move the slurry preparation. *the operator in this area adds pigment to the mixer or prepares slurry. *it would not be necessary to raise and remove the beaker from the mixer because it would pass to a lower container, which with a peristaltic pump would send the slurry to the applicator. *a pneumatic valve could be fitted at the bottom, which works very well with the slurry. 5 *the lower part of the mixer should be the cleaning point for the mixers and their lower containers, for which this area should be delimited to channel the waste and water generated. *also the water generated by the cleaning of the mixer and its hopper with high pressure water. *an accessible channelling system would have to be built from the final mixer area to the settling tanks *the slurry application assembly should also be modified, from receipt of the pallet at the cutter to delivery to the racker, with a set of mobile applicators and conveyors.. *it could be approached in 2 phases. phase i *. the current belt conveyor is transformed into 2 belt conveyors and one polycorrugated conveyor *the belt is not contaminated, as it is the side polycores that are contaminated. 6 phase ii *in this second phase, the applicators are made mobile and a central agitator tank is installed to prevent the slurry from settling and to collect the slurry left over from the application. *this allows the cleaning and maintenance of the assembly to be carried out outside the factory. * the conveyor of the main applicator can be made with a polycor or tc guide bench section in which the pallets go without space between them and driven by the belt conveyor at the exit of the cutting system.", "34.Operarios para produciòn de tejas.pdf": "operarios y funciones principales para planta de tejas:", "38.Problems with acrylic.pdf": "1 onur kiremit applicator paint. may 2023 2 applicator paint the wet application of paint should improve its current application, the amount of 20 grams of paint with 50% or 25% solids should not affect the application of paint on the side of the pallets (interlocking side), on the front side or on the bottom side of the pallet as much this paint contamination is transferred to the dirt in the corners of the racker. 3 4 this subsequently impacts on the bases and sides of the rack corners, with the pallet adhering to the rack corner after curing. in my opinion, the side, front and bottom application of the wet tile should be reduced: a) for the lateral application, change the position and the current angle of fixation of the paint gun, which affects this side or change to a “low pressure paint application system with 2 perpendicular nozzles”. b) for the front application, reduce the space between the moulds on the paint application conveyor (by reducing the speed of this conveyor, to avoid applying paint on the front of the lower part of the mould) and consider changing the inclination of the mould conveyor to raise it at the point of application of the tile. c) to reduce the lower contamination of the mould, the current conveyor would have to be shortened by 2 conveyors.", "44.REPORT ON THICKNESS AND WEIGHT MEASUREMENTS 281125.pdf": "1 report on thickness and weight measurements – double roman tile 281125 following a review of the measurements recorded for fresh tiles, the following assessments and control proposals are presented: a) initial process verification it is agreed that multiple measurements will be taken at the start of production (09:00) to verify that thicknesses—including the q2 measurement—and weight conform to established specifications. b) control frequency and material management once the extrusion head is adjusted and stabilized, hourly controls will be implemented during production. concrete discarded during these verifications can be recycled by reintroducing it into the extruder hopper. c) analysis of discrepancies in data from 261125 an inconsistency is observed in the variations of thickness and weight recorded between 07:55 and 09:00 hours—with an unexplained increase in both values—unless the height of the extrusion box was modified (a change that must be recorded in the production report) or a sudden variation in the concrete's humidity occurred. it is equally inconsistent that the roller consumption (96) and push chain (83) values remain unchanged with identical thickness and weight measurements. the cause of this discrepancy must be investigated. d) complementary control on cured tiles the control in the wet state must be complemented with: *verification of measurements on cured tiles, to confirm that dimensional patterns are maintained. *sample installation of 10 tiles, to validate the correct interlocking of the upper and lower profiles—an aspect that thickness measurements cannot verify. e) breakage tests and dispatch criteria breakage tests on the machine are an essential indicator that must be monitored to evaluate product evolution and compare its performance before dispatch. tiles destined for roof installation should preferably have 2 f) roof breakage analysis to accurately determine the origin of breakages on site, it is essential to characterize the type of tile fracture, its angle, and the crack's point of origin. additionally, the thickness of the affected tiles must be measured and compared against reference values.", "45.NOTE ON SLIPPER WEAR CONTROL 031225.pdf": "1 note on slipper wear control – 031225 the corrective actions and measurement procedures for slipper wear control are detailed below: a) reference value update as indicated by riccardo, it is necessary to update the reference value for measurement wbss2 in the excel database, setting it to 23.5 mm. 2 b) definition and marking of measurement points to ensure repeatability, reference lines (see blue lines on the drawing) must be marked on the brackets of the big slipper and the small slipper. these measurement points should generally be located at the center of each flat surface and curve (except at the ends). the fundamental criterion is that they allow for consistent measurements. c) verification of the big slipper's position the position of the big slipper relative to its outer bracket (indicated with red circles on the drawing) must be verified and recorded to ensure it is always the same. in the case of the reference drawing, the distances are:  wave profile side: 2.2 mm  assembly side: 1.5 mm this alignment is crucial to avoid stressing the mounting bracket. 3 d) measurement procedure for the big slipper the ends of the big slipper, corresponding to positions wsb0 and wsb6/wsb7 (e.g., wsb0 = 34.51 mm, wsb7 = 37.56 mm), must be measured. as they are located outside the mounting bracket, these measurements can be taken directly from the exterior using a 150 mm vernier caliper. fundamental principle: after each installation or startup, the reference measurements taken on the big and small slippers must be identical to the established standard values, there by ensuring process consistency.", "46.c ROMAN WET TILE Measurements 051225.pdf": "roman wet tile (wienerberger) q.1 q.2 q.3 q.4 q.5 q.6 nominal 8 11 11,9 11,1 11,9 9,6 range 9 12 12,9 12,1 12,9 10,6 theorical date: 05/12/2025 operator: weight 4,570 gr time q.1 q.2 q.3 q.4 q.5 q.6 4,520 gr 7:00 8:00 9:00 10:00 11:00 12:00 13:00 14:00 15:00 16:00 17:00 18:00 19:00 20:00 21:00 22:00 23:00 0:00 1:00 2:00 3:00 4:00 5:00 6:00 7:00", "46.Work procedure Wet Tile Measurement Control 2025 051225 1122.pdf": "date: 05/12/ 2025 page: 1 of 2 n drawing 1 2 3 4 5 6 the markings on the tile can be increased to more than two in order to ensure a more precise and straight cutting line during the manual incision with the blade. perform the manual incision with the blade as perpendicular as possible to the tile surface. 5. insert the blade into the tile to separate the surfaces, allowing for thickness measurement in the next step. wienerberger hungary work procedure tile measurement control wet tile measurement control… steps key points 1. at 60-minute intervals, one tile shall be taken from the production line. the initial samples must correspond to the start of production or a model change. inspect the back side of the mould for any deformation, concrete residue, or wear that may affect the dimensional quality of the tile. 2. each sample shall be placed on the scale to record its weight. the net weight of the tile shall be determined after weighing the assembly and, depending on the type of scale available, it may be read directly or require a mathematical operation (subtraction of the mould's weight). 6. use the blade to displace the upper concrete from the mould outwards, enabling the placement of the depth gauge to measure the thickness of the designated section. digital depht gauge 4. mark two points on the exterior of the tile, 70 mm from the mould end, using a pointed scriber to define the cutting line. 3. position the tile and mould on a flat surface to facilitate handling. the following are required: *a table or flat work surface at an adequate height to perform thickness measurements comfortably and accurately. *a scale properly positioned in close proximity to the extruder to streamline the weighing process. date: 05/12/ 2025 page: 2 of 2 n drawing 7 8 9 10 11 12 ensure perfect alignment of the digital depth gauge with the cylindrical bar (10 mm diameter x 200 mm length), maintaining its perpendicularity to the mould. the initial thickness and weight values are theoretical. the optimal values and their working tolerances will be determined based on the raw materials used and the specific curing process at each factory. these values and measurements serve as the reference standards for wet tile control, which will be supplemented by subsequent controls performed once the cured tile. by weighing the assembly (tile + mould) and then the empty mould, the net weight of the tile can be obtained. the exact method (direct tare or subtraction) depends on the type of scale, as detailed in point 3. ensure the digital depth gauge is perfectly aligned with the calibrated bars (10x10x200 mm) and maintains perpendicularity to the mould. 7. prepare the wet tile for thickness measurement as illustrated in the reference image. tools used: *calibrated square bar, 10 mm x 10 mm x 200 mm. *calibrated cylindrical bar, 10 mm diameter x 200 mm length. *spatula. wienerberger hungary work procedure tile measurement control wet tile measurement control… steps key points 8. for measuring q1, a cylindrical bar shall be used to avoid deforming the concrete or altering the measurement. once measured, subtract the 10 mm diameter of the bar. 10. once thickness measurements are completed, weigh the empty mould. 11. record the results in the extruder control sheet. 12. adjust weights and thicknesses to meet the specifications set by the central laboratory. if variations are observed, adjust the extruder head and repeat steps 1 to 12 of this procedure. 9. for measuring points q2, q3, q4, q5, and q6, a calibrated bar shall be used to prevent deformation. after measurement, subtract the 10 mm of the bar.", "46a.WET TILE THICKNESS CONTROL PROCEDURE 051225.pdf": "wet tile thickness control procedure 051225 1. definition and purpose thickness measurement constitutes a fundamental parameter in production control. its main objective is to ensure that each tile complies with the established reference dimensions and weight, thereby guaranteeing a consistent level of product quality. 2. internal control procedure (quality) a systematic control will be implemented through hourly measurements during production, applied to all profiles of the tile. 3. specific control objectives these measurements allow for: *verifying extruder adjustment: confirming that the extrusion box is correctly configured to achieve the target thickness and weight. *validating component alignment: checking that the relative position between the small slipper and the big slipper is correct, in order to prevent future issues in the interlocking and installation of tiles on the roof. *monitoring slipper wear: identifying progressive wear on the profile of the slippers at the extruder outlet. this wear is directly reflected in the upper profile of the tile during production, causing its deformation and a generalized increase in thickness and weight. it serves as a key indicator for preventive maintenance. *monitoring roller wear: the wear on the big roller and small roller is identified by measuring the diameters at their predefined reference zones.", "46b.INSTRUMENTS AND ACCESSORIES FOR THICKNESS MEASUREMENT 051225.pdf": "1 instruments and accessories for thickness measurement 051225 to perform thickness measurements on wet tiles, the following equipment is recommended:  a profile-adjusted cutting blade: it must be precisely adapted to the tile's cross- section at the measurement point. typically, this cut is made between 60 and 100 mm from the tile's end, depending on the specific mould and profile. for the roman tile, the recommended initial cutting position is 70 mm, due to the stability of thicknesses in that section of the mould. the blade should incorporate a rubber reinforcement on its top part to facilitate and stabilize the incision into the tile. 2  a precision caliper: the use of a depth gauge is recommended, although a 150 mm vernier caliper (analog or digital) is also suitable.  calibrated reference rods: o a cylindrical steel rod, 10 mm in diameter and 200 mm in length. o a square steel rod, 10 mm per side and 200 mm in length.", "14.Comments on TC slippers adjustment for Abece line.pdf": "comentarios sobre los videos de diamond 220920 se inicia con ajuste de altura con el calibre, sobre la bancada para conseguir una horizontalidad inicial . falta el valor h , para el proceso del montaje de rodillos y zapatas. no hay referencias de la posición de partida de los tornillos de apoyo y ajuste para las alturas e inclinaciones de las zapatas, se inicia con las posiciones del último ajuste realizado de las zapatas. falta los valores ( 1 al 8 ) para el proceso del montaje de rodillos y zapatas. acomodación de la zapata grande a los tornillos de ajuste e inclinación de la zapata del soporte base de fijación. primera acomodación y comprobación alineamiento de la zapata y rodillo grande con la escuadra comprobar la altura del plano de la zapata grande lado onda a la base del soporte de fijación comprobar la altura del plano de la zapata grande lado ensamble a la base del soporte de fijación falta el valor f4 para el proceso del montaje de rodillos y zapatas. comprobar la altura e inclinación zapata grande lado onda 1 comprobar la altura e inclinación zapata grande plano lado onda 2 comprobar la altura e inclinación de la zapata grande lado central 3 comprobar la altura e inclinación de la zapata grande plano lado ensamble 4 falta los valores c4, b4 y el valor g4 para el proceso del montaje de rodillos y zapatas. atornillar y fijar la zapata grande al soporte base comprobar la altura e inclinación de la zapata grande plano lado onda 2 falta los valores c2, b2, para el proceso del montaje de rodillos y zapatas. comprobara la altura e inclinación de la zapata grande plano lado ensamble 4 comprobar la medida del gap entre rodillo y zapata en onda central 3 falta los valores g1, g2, g3 y el valor g4 para el proceso del montaje de rodillos y zapatas. comprobar la medida del gap entre rodillo y zapata en el plano lado ensamble onda 4 falta el valor g4 para el proceso del montaje de rodillos y zapatas. ajustar de nuevo los tornillos de apoyo y fijación zapata grande reapretar de nuevo los tornillos de fijación de la zapata al soporte. revisión alturas e inclinaciones lado onda 1. revisión alturas e inclinaciones plano lado onda 2. falta los valores c2 y b2 para el proceso del montaje de rodillos y zapatas. revisión alturas e inclinaciones plano lado onda lado ensamble 4. falta los valores c4 y b4 para el proceso del montaje de rodillos y zapatas. revisión altura del plano lado onda de la zapata a la base del soporte de fijación de la zapata 2 falta los valores d1, d3, d5 y el valor f2 para el proceso del montaje de rodillos y zapatas. revisión de la altura del plano lado onda de la zapata a la base del soporte de fijación de la zapata 4 falta el valor f4 para el proceso del montaje de rodillos y zapatas. reapriete final de los 2 tornillos de fijación de la zapata grande al soporte de la zapatas. acomodación de la zapata pequeña a la grande reapriete inicial de los 2 tornillos de fijación a la zapata grande con la llave de tubo. final del reapriete inicial de los 2 tornillos de fijación a la zapata grande con la llave de tubo. verificación con calibre de la altura de la zapata pequeña con respecto a la grande con el martillo metálico desplaza hacia abajo la punta de la zapata pequeña al rodillo. ajuste de los 2 tornillos de apoyo del soporte para la inclinación de la zapata pequeña. nueva verificación con calibre de la altura de la zapata pequeña con respecto a la grande. nuevo ajuste con el martillo metálico de la punta de la zapata pequeña al rodillo. ajuste tornillos de apoyo del soporte para la inclinación de la zapata pequeña. nueva comprobación del ajuste de altura e inclinación de la zapata pequeña. nuevo ajuste manual de altura e inclinación de la zapata pequeña. nuevo apriete para bloqueo de la zapata pequeña con la grande. nueva verificación de la altura con calibre de la zapata pequeña respecto a la grande nueva verificación de la altura e inclinación de la zapata pequeña. n falta valores de ci y bi para el proceso del montaje de rodillos y zapatas verificación final del montaje de las zapatas y los rodillos comprobación de giro para comprobar que no hay rozamiento. falta los valores para el proceso del montaje de rodillos y zapatas de la g1 a la gi v definición de las referencias utilizadas en este proceso: h- valor para adecuar a la horizontalidad de la estructura basculante para el montaje del soporte de las zapatas y rodillos. c- valor del gap en las líneas de referencia( 1-5 ), entre la parte final de la zapata grande a la escuadra utilizada en el montaje. b- valor del gap en las líneas de referencia ( 1-5 ), entre la parte inicial de la zapata grande a la escuadra utilizada en el montaje. ci- valor del gap en la línea de referencia ,entre la parte final de la zapata pequeña a la escuadra utilizada en el montaje. bi- valor del gap en la línea de referencia, entre la parte inicial de la zapata pequeña a la escuadra utilizada en el montaje. d- valor del gap en las líneas de referencia( 1-5 ) ,entre la parte final de la zapata grande al soporte de fijación de la zapata. f- valor del gap en las líneas de referencia( 1-5 ), entre la parte plana de la zapata grande a la base del soporte de fijación de la zapata. g- valor del gap en las líneas de referencia( 1-5 ), entre la parte interior de la zapata grande al rodillo grande. gi- valor del gap en la línea de referencia entre, la parte interior zona plaza de la zapata interior al rodillo pequeño. los valores que serían necesarios para definir un proceso de montaje de rodillos y zapatas son: h. (medido con calibre) c1, c2, c3, c4, c5. (medido con galgas) b1, b2, b3, b4, b5. (medido con galgas) ci. (medido con galgas) bi. (medido con galgas) d1, d2, d3, d4, d5 = . (medido con calibre) debe ser un solo único valor. f1, f2, f3, f4, f5. . (medido con calibre) g1, g2, g3, g4, g5. (medido con galgas) gi. (medido con galgas) conclusiones del montaje: a) nuestro ajuste inicial de paralelismo con la bancada que se hace con las partes planas del rodillo, ellos posicionan a un valor h, en la bancada con un tornillo de ajuste y otro de tope en las partes delanteras, que luego utilizan para aumentar o disminuir el peso y otros 2 tornillos en ambas partes traseras, las cuales quedan fijas. b) el ajuste del comparador de las alturas c y b, las realizan con el apoyo de la escuadra en el soporte de zapatas y el contacto con el rodillo, los gaps que se originan entre la línea de la escuadra y las zapatas son las alturas, todo a nivel visual, por lo menos en el video no se identifica otra comprobación. c) el ajuste del gap g entre las zapatas y los rodillos, también es a nivel visual y es el que resulta del ajuste de las alturas c y b. conclusiones de la puesta en marcha : 1) mueven y regulan las alturas de todo el conjunto de zapatas para subir o bajar el peso de la teja con los tornillos delanteras de su bancada con la línea de fabricación en marcha o parada. 2) cambian y regulan las inclinaciones de las zapatas con la línea de fabricación en marcha o parada. debería haber un protocolo claro y definido sobre esas actuaciones de cara a no tener problemas de una posible rotura de las zapatas de widia que puedan instalarse en esa fábrica. miguel blanes canut arganda del rey 240920", "17.Adjusting a coupling big roller with big slipper.pdf": "1 setting position and initial checks, with the roller and big slipper widhts identified at the factory (300,1mm big roller & 300mm big slipper): we always consider 3 possible contact zones i of rollers and slippers. adjusting a coupling big roller with big slipper: 2 first check with the big slipper only, entering the space allowed by the big roller, checking the effort to enter the big slipper into the space of the big roller. moving the shaft left/right until the best centred position is found. 3 4 once in this position, if it is possible to turn the shaft by hand to identify if there are uniform or discontinuous frictions in the shaft rotation (big roller / big slipper), in case it is not possible to turn it properly, move on to the action of supplementing the 0.3 mm steel sheet. in case of doubt, check the eccentricity of the shaft, in this case about small roller . 5 sometimes, due to the high effort of the roller rotation gear box on the side of the interlock, oscillations can occur in the ucf211 bearing bracket and it may have to be replaced by a new one 6 if the test has shown no appreciable oscillations, mount the small slipper in the slipper holder and place it on the extruder. once the gear-motor has been assembled and installed, we will check the friction during rotation at its foreseen working speed using the grease cord test. this involves placing a continuous line of grease on the rollers along their entire upper part and, as the shaft rotates, any area that comes into contact with the roller to the slipper will drag the grease from that area and the points of contact will be easily detectable. 7 once it has rotated continuously, we can identify in which areas and points it has grazed the most. especially in the 3 most critical areas: 8 this test will identify the types of friction that exist between rollers and slippers or between the slippers and the side discs. if it is considered that the friction of the slipper with the roller and the side disc is excessive due to the cleanliness of both sides, we will supplement only 0.3 mm between rollers. supplement steel sheet 0.3 mm. if it is identified that the friction between the big slipper and the roller is excessive, the 0.3 mm between the rollers should be supplemented. 9 i don't think it is necessary to add more space between the rollers, as the excess slack will create dirt and concrete sticking to the sides of the mould when it comes out of the extruder.", "35.Planteamiento zapata widia para cabezal ABECE.pdf": "contrasagoma “super coppo” en tegolaia widia (tc) identificación sobre la zapata grande con widia utilizada ahora, en el cabezal de la tejera, con su sistema de preparación, puntos de fijación, funcionamiento y ajuste de la zapata grande con pastillas de widia soldadas. se valoran los 2 puntos nuevos de fijación m10, que se adelantan, presupongo que para retrasar la zapata al ser ahora la zapata más larga del original. la zapata grande con las pastillas de widia soldadas, incrementa su longitud , siendo 135mm / 136 mm su longitud final. conjunto de zapatas grandes usadas y menos usadas. estas son las últimas piezas nuevas facilitadas por daga, con soporte base superior y zapata pequeña. con el complemento final de la zapata grande de widia “daga” la longitud corresponde a los 130 mm, siendo la misma longitud que las medidas de originales de la zapata grande. con todo lo evaluado e identificado anteriormente,se plantea la fijación de una zapata grande de widia con 4 casquillos y tornillos allen de fijación al soporte intermedio de 30 mm además con la fijación a la bancada actual con 2 tornillos de m14, según medidas y comprobaciones realizadas. planteamiento a desarrollado en fábrica con 4 casquillos m10. planteamiento alternativo b , también con 4 casquillos m10 ,en línea como viene haciéndose en las implantaciones generales, con las zapatas tc (widia). en las 2 opciones anteriores hay que mecanizar los laterales de la bancada de la tejera y realizar cajeados para los nuevos puntos de fijación de la placa soporte, 30 mm más hacia arriba. el soporte actual del portazapatas tiene la siuiente configuración . para la acomodación el soporte portazapatas, en las 2 opciones a y b, quedaría así, 30 mm más hacia arriba. arganda a 14 de noviembre 2022", "39.Notes on roller and slipper wear 141125.pdf": "1 1. rollers: the foundation of the process i consider the rollers to be the starting point, as their condition directly impacts the performance of the other components. big roller (wbr3/5): a maximum wear reference we typically use is around 6 mm on its flat areas. small roller (wsr7/8): similarly, the maximum wear reference is typically 5 mm on its flat areas. impact and relationship between components: if the ranges indicated in the table (128/128/121/117 mm) are not respected, two main issues may arise:  insufficient feeding: the material does not reach the slippers with adequate consistency.  accelerated wear of the slippers: without proper preforming, the slippers are forced to work harder in the final shaping, significantly reducing their lifespan. 2 2. slippers: defining the final product for slippers, the criteria must be more rigorous, as they are directly responsible for the final upper profile of the tile. big slipper (wsb3/5): the maximum wear reference typically considered is ≈ 1.5 mm in the deformation of the tile's upper profile. small slipper (wssb1/2): similarly, ≈ 1.5 mm (in practice, this is even more critical for the reasons explained below). consequences of wear and replacement criteria: when the big slipper (wsb3/5) progressively alters the upper profile of the tile, it creates a fitting issue, as illustrated in the following photo. although this corresponds to a profile different from the double roman, it serves as a valid representation of the effect: 3 the lower profile (defined by the mould) is fixed and invariable. the upper profile, shaped by the worn big slipper, increases the tile thickness and creates gaps in the overlap once installed on the roof. this misalignment typically has two critical consequences:  loss of watertightness: the gaps allow water ingress, compromising the primary function of the roof.  replacement criterion: the decision to replace should not be based solely on a measurement of slipper wear but on the loss of the optimal profile. to determine the acceptable wear range and the maximum tolerable deformation, the following checks could be carried out:  inspection and monitoring of slipper wear, comparing it with the reference ranges (38.5/38.5/21/22/16 mm).  assembly of test roof sections with the produced tiles to visually and functionally assess the extent of admissible deformation and establish the correct reference range for each case.  as a complementary measure, it may be appropriate to use a control gauge to help define and quickly verify the maximum allowable surface deformation. for its part, the small slipper (wssb1/2) is equally critical. its wear, by also increasing the tile thickness, reduces the clearance in the fitting. in my experience, this can lead to breakage issues when walking on the roof. 4 key relationship between components: based on accumulated experience, the following wear relationship in component lifespan is typically observed: for every 1 big roller worn, 2 small rollers are usually worn. for every 1 big roller worn, 2 big slippers are usually worn. for every 1 small roller worn, 2 small slippers are usually worn. in other words, as a general rule, the lifespan of a set typically corresponds to: 1 big roller, 2 small rollers, 2 big slippers, and 4 small slippers. this chain relationship underscores the importance of coordinated preventive maintenance: uncontrolled wear in the rollers has a multiplier effect and accelerates the wear of the slippers. conclusion keeping both slippers and slippers within verified wear ranges—always adapted to the specific raw materials of each factory—is not just about extending the lifespan of the parts. i believe it is the most robust strategy for ensuring the final product quality, preventing water ingress, and avoiding future breakages during installation and roof maintenance.", "9.Considerations on problems with Abece TC Slippers.pdf": "breakage of ct-5 tc big slipper – meeting 09/07/21 additional comments after those of last meeting: shim plate and overpressure on upper screws of the tc small slipper. talking about lateral fixing between tc big slipper and tc small slipper: pero una vez fijada la zapata pequeña a la grande, se generan unas marcas en el “bush” que a veces están en el tornillo 1 o en el 2 o en ambos 1 y 2. estas marcas en el bush se generan por la posición final de la zapata pequeña en el ajuste de la altura e inclinación con respecto a la zapata grande, la posición final de los cajeados de fijación de la zapata pequeña con respecto al “bush” y la fuerza de apriete del operario al fijar los tornillos para sujetar la zapata pequeña. además del exceso de presión superior comentado el día anterior, se puede generar otro exceso de presión lateral hacia al exterior de la zapata grande. en esta hipotesis que se plantea, el problema de la rotura de la zapata grande de widia puede estar facilitado por la tolerancia lateral actual por el tornillo m10 a la fijación de la zapata pequeña sobre los 14 mm de la anchura de los cajeados (tolerancia máxima 4,2 mm) . junto con el diámetro de 15 mm del “bush” al apretar con el tornillo permite crear presión lateral hacia la derecha de la zapata grande de widia, que será mayor o menor presión según la marca que nos encontramos en el bush, facilitando el riesgo de rotura en esa zona. este exceso de presión por el tornillo 2 forzaría el “bush” hacia la parte lateral derecha de la zapata de widia , (es la parte con menor espesor en esa dirección 7,5 mm) que con el resto de presiones podría provocar la rotura de la zapata. para evitar este sobre esfuerzo habría que reducir la anchura de los cajeados a lo minimo posible 11 / 12 mm, habría que comprobarlo para que permitiera realizar toda la inclinación necesaria en la zapata pequeña. “otra idea como solución provisional”, en línea a reducir la anchura del cajeado sería colocar unos bloqueadores laterales ,en los cajeados para evitar esas marcas en el “bush” o excesos de presión lateral.. primero se coloca la zapata en su posición, posteriormente en función de la holgura lateral del tornillo en el cajeado, se suplementa con la pletina tratada “21 x 13 de 2 ”, todas las medidas son orientativas a comprobar realmente en la fábrica. arganda del rey 090721 planteamiento de la fijación con casquillos en la zapata pequeña después de haber estudiado varias posibilidades para evitar las sobrepresiones en la fijación de la zapata pequeña a la grande, hemos desarrollado el planteamiento en base a unos casquillos para la fijación de la zapata pequeña sobre la grande para limitar el efecto de sobre presión, que se puede estar produciendo en esa zona y que en el último video llamada ya hicimos referencia y que os presentamos para vuestra evaluación y valoración. el planteamiento inicial que planteamos como alternativa era este el planteamiento desarrollado, ha sido en base a 2 casquillos con un acero 39nicrmo3 para obtener una mayor resistencia, con un diámetro exterior de 13,5 mm y el interior de 10,5 mm , con la longitud de 21 mm. a) para evaluar y valorar la nueva fijación con los casquillos, se ha realizado un montaje con la zapata pequeña con las alturas indicadas en vuestra información. como resultado podemos indicar que queda limitado el desplazamiento hacia delante y atrás de la zapata pequeña en relación a la zapata grande sobre 0,8 mm, en el desplazamiento hacia la parte inferior puede pasar de 11.0 mm a 18.0 mm ( 7 mm de desplazamiento) lo cual permite realizar si fuera necesario una inclinación de más de 2 mm. “ante lo cual consideramos que, con el planteamiento de los casquillos, nos permite los ajustes necesarios para producir tejas con normalidad. “ b) en la fijación y posicionamiento de la zapata pequeña sobre la zapata grande en los ajustes de las alturas facilitadas, consideramos que el trabajar con las arandelas planas comerciales de m10 con espesor de 2 mm y diámetro exterior 20 mm sería critico en algunos ajustes de la zapata pequeña, por lo que proponemos si comercialmente es posible o se puede fabricar una arandela especial con diámetro exterior 22 / 23 mm, siempre que no toque la base inferior de la zapata pequeña o utilizar la shim plate de 2 mm, que estaban utilizando con anchura máxima de 22/23 mm siempre que no toque la base de la zapata pequeña. indicamos 22 / 23 mm y de 2 mm de espesor , porque en el ajuste realizado en nuestro montaje, según sus indicaciones de altura, no tenía mucho más holgura en la parte inferior. ( no obstante, hay que comprobarlo en el montaje en fábrica) shim plate con una altura máxima de 22/23mm con el espesor de 2 mm. arganda del rey 230721", "25.Ridge packer evaulations at customer site.pdf": "13 packaging *in this installation there are 3 or 4 critical points to evaluate: 1) forming packages of 4 tiles, the tiles are not well aligned. (they should be aligned as the bundle is being formed or when strapping). 14 *see the possibility of aligning the tiles in the formation of the package. 2)*when strapping the packages of 4 tiles, they do not fit well, the strap seems to me too rigid and does not fit, for the arch of the 4 tiles, (poorly fitted and poorly welded/not aligned). 15 *see the possibility of aligning the tiles in the strapping of the package. 3) *when forming the bundle there is excessive slippage and shock at the base of the tiles, generating friction and loosening the bundle. (when forming the bundle, if it is poorly welded or not tightened, the bundle becomes unstable). (it would have to be placed from lower / lower height). 16 4)* when the packet is formed, there is free space between the packets, when they are left on the plastic base. (you should help them to fit closer together as they are arranged). 4)* when placing the vertical bundles for horizontal strapping, the bundles are pushed backwards and tip over. (the \"most compact bundle\" is formed or \"the tiles must be followed up to the strapping position\".) 17 thermoshrinking 1) *in the palletising of the ridge tile, the strapping of the loose packages is identified, in my opinion for ridge tile to have a better hold, the plastic bag should be closed and shrink-wrapped at the top, if it has excess moisture, with holes in the plastic, to avoid moisture inside the bag.", "32.Starting new plant checking list.pdf": "values and positions of the facilities for monitoring the “processes” in order to monitor all the processes in a factory, we need to control the values and positions of each piece of equipment, which may vary in value, such as (pressure, speed, etc.) or by the position in its regulation (start or stop control sensors, etc.) or their movement, such as (linear displacements, turns, etc.) when starting up a factory it is very important to have \"references of the starting points of all the components\" to make checks with time, in case they have been modified with the work or there have been changes, without notifying them. for this we need to mark/signal and have all the information updated in all processes. extruder general : pressure signalling general, regulator for extruder feed. push chain signalling : list trolleys. anti-lifting cylinder piston detectors. pressure on pressure regulator manometer anti-lift system measurements: situation of each polycord of the trolleys. measurements between pushers on both sides. tensioners on both sides of the push chain tile cutting system signalling in the cutting system : positioning of push chain axis with carriage arm plate. positioning of the cutting cam. positioning of detector on safety piston. positioning of reduction axis with up and down cutting carriage disc. measurements : distance between cutting arm bearings from eccentric to cutting carriage axis. distance between the sides of the cutting carriage in the cutting position. fresh tile/mould conveyors extruder t1 output conveyor write down : speed of the t1 polycord. transporter output extruder t2 write down : speed of the t2 polycore. signalling: pressure on pressure gauge regulator, system blowers cleaning surface tile rotary general : pressure signalling general, regulator for rotary. racker conveyor write down : speed of the racker polycord input conveyor. signalling: positioning of transmitter and receiver photocell supports (length, height and inclination) on conveyor. racker stacker chain write down : time to go up. signaling: list angles of right side of stacking chain positioning of the input photocell supports for the chain, transmitter and receiver (length, height and inclination) disc and cams detector upstacker stop. stacker stop detector (height) positioning of the safety limit switch during the ascent. measurement: polycord plane on angle flats on each side positioning of the fixing studs of the support guides of the stacker chain. studs for tensioning the stacking chain on each side. step gate signalling: cylinder detector for open and closed gates. cylinder axis positioning / gate system bearing. cylinder clamping bolt positioning. fixed step stacker signalling: detector or photocell pass tile/mould sq37.8 pressure regulator for gate cylinder supply. stacker pusher arm signalling: cylinder supply pressure regulator. cylinder up and down arm pressure regulator. positioning of the arm at the front and at the back. racker unstacking chain write down : time of descent. signaling: list angles of the left or right side (depending on the assistance area) of the destacking chain disk and cams detecting the lowering of the destacker (height) unloaded destacker chain positioning detector (height) safety end of stroke positioning at the destacking chain infeed. measurement: polycord plane on flats of the unloading chain angles on each side positioning of the fixing studs of the support guides of the destacking chain. denester chain tensioning studs on each side. rotary turning system write down : rotary turn advance time. oil control unit pressure for feed. signaling: list centering plates of the rotary. positioning of each plate , to evaluate evolution. feed position and arrival of the rotary slide. positioning of the left, central and right detector of the turning carriage. position of the detector in front and behind the locking cylinder switchboard maintenance oil level. measurement: diameter of support wheels , for each plate. cylinder axis , rotary cylinder shaft in and out. pusher-destacker arm signalling: positioning of the arm in front and behind. positioning of the forward and backward arm limit switch. positioning of the denester arm detector. unstacking conveyor write down : speed of the polycord unstacking conveyor. signalling: lateral centering guides of the mould exit conveyor. positioning of the transmitter and receiver photocell supports. ( length, height and inclination ) jamming on the conveyor. tile / mould conveyors exit conveyor destacker write down : speed of the polycarrier exit destacker. conveyor entrance unstacker write down : speed of polycord conveyor for demoulding input. mould conveyors demoulding moulds exit conveyor i write down : speed of the polycord conveyor for tile outlet moulds i. demoulding moulds exit conveyor ii write down : speed of the polycord conveyor for tile outlet moulds ii.", "33.Roof tile plant overall evaluation & suggestions.pdf": "1 report northstone 160323 from my visit to the northstone (antrim) factory from 14 to 16 march 2023, i give my assessment and recommendations on the different equipment and processes that i have been able to review. sand hoppers / belt conveyors, cement silos, pigment dispenser very good equipments and installation. mixer: r24 erich, it´s a very good mixer. liquid to avoid concrete incrustations in the mixer once the inside of the mixer has been cleaned, it is advisable to impregnate this liquid (zetolan-mek 3 ) with the exterior of all the elements that may come into contact with the concrete of the mixer, thereby avoiding the incrustations and the ones that are generated can be easily cleaned metal detector i recommend the use of a metal detector, the closed loop metal detector is the best for this application.to detect a 10 mm nut, to avoid breakage of the slipper, roller or mould, it must be tested every week. or mould, it is necessary to test its operation every week 2 pallets aluminium : capacity pallets, 7 chambers 39.200 donard, 3 chambers 16.800 causeway, 4 chambers 22.400 derrie pallets. side moulds all very clean and on the surface with some easy to clean dirt. on the top of the donard mould some small concrete adherence, no problema. it also has wear on the corner due to contact with the mould release palleter blades. no pallet side scrapers act, if there are no concrete adherence they are not necessary. 3 pallets flow inverter. the polycords of the lower outlet conveyor are quite damaged, so it would be necessary to consider the replacement conveyors line pallets flow inverter to extruder i recommend to identify wear of the guides, polycords and pulleys, in order to evaluate the replacement before a production line shutdown. flaps pallets based on comments in profile changes on the accommodation or adjustment of the flap,i recomend, possible change of the screen system for each model to a fixed non- adjustable one. oil applicator. 4 position of the oil applicator. i recommend the study and evaluation to move the oil applicator forward, at the start of the infeed conveyor, making the conveyor area independent of the applicator and replacing the infeed rollers with a base with bench guides to allow the pallets to move at the infeed of the pusher chain. pallets pushing system it is necessary to check daily the areas where the carriages are pushed to the pallet and their bearings. it is also advisable to clean the chain with” low pressure air”, but “not to grease it”. check monthly ¿? the distance between pusher fingers, today it measures 421 mm. position of the pallet pushing system given the changes of guides and adjustments in the use of the 3 tile profiles every day and the future non-use of the space between the pushing systhem and the extruder head, i recommend the study and evaluation with vortex to move the pushing systhem forward by 1,260 mm. this would eliminate the anti-lifting system of the pallets, reduce the bed lateral guides and reduce the length of the bar that moves the cutting system. temporarily, a base with guides could be placed in this area so that the pallets only move along the base and laterally guided to the entrance of the extruder head. 5 anti-lifting system of the pallets at the moment it does not work with the donard / caseway pallets, therefore, with the use of the 3 profiles, i recommend the study and evaluation of the possible placement of polyuretane wheels with tensor that circulate through the valley areas of the derrie pallet, which has little difference in height with the bases of the donard / caseway 6 extruder head the adjustment values of the donard / causeway models with tugnsten (tc) rollers and slippers have been identified with the factory operators, as well as with the derrie model which uses steel rollers and slippers. i recommend the study and evaluation of modifying one area of the causeway tile interlocking from straight to curved. hopper extruder. i recommend increasing the concrete column in the extruder, to guarantee the feeding of concrete to the roller and slipper. cutting system study and evaluate the possible application of a frontal knife water and air nozzle (currently only lateral) in the production of causeway tiles on the rounded cut area. 7 check the protections of the belt that drives the cutting blades, as it vibrates a lot and causes excessive noise. polycord conveyors at the extruder to two rackers . loading conveyor for two rackers to identify wear of the guides, polycords and pulleys, in order to evaluate the replacement before a stop of the production line. rackers (4 tiles - 35 floors) some racks need to be checked for cleanliness and deterioration, the paint on the top guides is lifting off some of them. double loading pusher (76.2 pitch) for racks plant it is necessary to fit rubber buffers as a stopper at the front and rear stops of the 2 pushers or reduce current shocks. racker - 35 floors all guides must be checked for cleanliness and deterioration. check the tensioning to be equal and the chain measurement to check its elongation initially the measurement corresponds to ( 102 \" = 2590,8 mm). checked the 150323 the measurement is 2595 mm (+4.2 mm), in the 4 chains of the rackers. the initial position of the front racker is higher than the rear racker ( + 8 mm), it is interesting to follow up. roller-way for racks circulation in the chambers extractor for racks racks loading/unloading roller-waywet tiles racks transfer unit and transfer car loading 8 racks advancement group dry tiles transfer car unloading and rack transfer to the unloading line wet tiles racks pusher in the chambers the positioning of the racks in their stations must be ensured, especially in the loading and unloading positions of the fresh and dry tile racks. dry and wet tiles transfer cars in my opinion, the fresh tile transfer has some shaft / bearing problems in some of the wheels, it makes a noise out of the ordinary compared to the cured tile transfer. 14 curing chambers i do not have the time to evaluate the water in the base of the chambers, nor to assess the current curing cycles. unloading pusher it is necessary to fit rubber buffers as a stopper at the front and rear stops of the 2 pushers or reduce current shocks. 9 tiles deracker (4 tiles - 35 floors) all guides should be checked for cleanliness and deterioration. check tensioning to ensure that it is equal and the chain measurement to check its elongation chain, the initially the measurement corresponds to ( 102 \" = 2590.8 mm). checked the 150323 the measurement is 2,602 mm (+11.8 mm), on the 2 deracker chains. it was not possible to check the initial position because there was no racker to check the difference in height and make a follow-up. l= 5000 unloading conveyor identify wear of the wheels, polycords and pulleys, in order to evaluate the replacement before a stop of the production line. “t150” depalleter regarding the adjustments of the depalleter machine for the 3 tile profiles, depending on the current pallet conveyor, the only thing i would consider is a study and evaluation of the accommodation of a pre-depalleter unit at the entrance of the current conveyor, with guides and adjustable for each model. 10 polycord conveyors from depalleter to pallets flowinverter. identify wear of the guides, polycords and pulleys, in order to evaluate the replacement before a stop of the production line. polycord conveyors from depalleter to paint applicator. identify wear of the guides, polycords and pulleys, in order to evaluate the replacement before a stop of the production line. depending on the contamination of water with paint on the conveyor sections throughout the area, i would consider the study and assessment of reducing the length of the conveyor where the paint is applied to the minimum necessary. applying the paint “only” at the entrance of the conveyor to help reduce the length of the conveyor and distance the operator's application from the selection of tiles. redirect all conveyor cleaning wáter /paint discharges to a central tank. delimit the area of possible contamination on the ground with a 5 / 10 cm high fence. 11 polycord conveyors from paint applicator to dry rotary. identify wear of the guides, polycords and pulleys, in order to evaluate the replacement before a stop of the production line. drying rotary 40 floors heavy wear on all the guides, they need to be replaced. racker 50 floors all guides must be checked for cleanliness and deterioration. check the tensioning to be equal and the chain measurement to check its elongation. unloading pusher drying rotary double loading pusher drying rotary (donard / caseway) it is necessary to fit rubber buffers as a stopper or reduce current shocks maintenance. the following are some of the maintenance and efficiency assessments that i'm sure some of them apply to this factory, but i always like to point them out. i don't know the planning and maintenance history, in relation to the equipment must be high, preventive maintenance is necessary and the lubrication routes. each operator should carry out a minimum level of preventive maintenance and, depending on the level of knowledge, some basic corrective maintenance work. 12 as a general rule in the factories that i have worked in, to achieve and keep high efficiency, by 1 hour of production needs 1 hour of maintenance at the end of the daily production. when the time of a production stoppage is more than 15 minutes, it should be necessary to study it and monitor it in order to propose a solution or to avoid the occurrence of this high stoppage time. in order to increase efficiency, it is necessary to provide a solution to the continuous stoppages of the installation, with the identification of the stoppages, their analysis and possible improvements that solve these stoppages with the participation of the entire production team of the factory. “5 whys “it is the problem-solving method used by exploring the underlying cause and effect of certain problems. the main objective is to determine the root cause of a defect or problem by successively asking the question \"why? summary this factory produces very good quality tiles, the efficiency can be improved with more maintenance and solving the problems of the current shutdowns. from my experience with 3 daily profiles, the average efficiency loss is 9 to 12 %. i recommend 2 production shifts, with a total of 16 hours of production and maintenance 2 officers at night 16 hours. to keep a high efficiency with a production of 20 hours for 5 days, you need a minimum of 2 cleaners 8 hours and 2 mechanics 8 hours at night and maintenance on saturday 8 hours 5 mechanics, with the possible support of an external workshop. i hope that my suggestions and advice can be useful, to increase the efficiency of the factory. antrim 160323", "43.TECHNICAL IMPROVEMENT PROPOSAL FOR ROTARY SYSTEM 201125.pdf": "1 1. modification of the front enclosure in the loading/unloading zone (racker and deracker) current situation: • the racker and deracker areas are located within the rotary's internal enclosure, sharing the same ambient air as the curing chamber. • as a result, temperature and humidity spikes during tile loading directly and negatively impact the racker and deracker zones. 2 • the current setup allows visibility into the rotary's interior from the lateral access points of the racker and deracker. proposed modification: to eliminate the existing external enclosure, the following steps are proposed: 1. install insulating panels in the interior areas defining the enclosure. 3 2. incorporate rubber seals on the top and sides of the insulating panels to improve sealing. 3. optionally, include access doors in the panels for maintenance purposes. 4. once the interior enclosure is completed, proceed with the removal of the external front and side panels. 4 2. ambient humidity control system for curing current issues: • 100% relative humidity inside the rotary. • condensation leading to water dripping from the ceiling onto the tiles. • tile surface damage and excessive moisture in the connection boxes. proposed solution: installation of a control system with the following features: • centralized controller with humidity sensors. • activation threshold: 98% relative humidity. • two alternative systems for extracting humidity to the exterior. • objective: prevent humidity from reaching 100%. 3. humidity extraction systems in the rotary two systems are available for humidity control in the rotary: 1. installation of extraction fans on the ceiling: a conventional system involving the placement of specialized fans at the top of the chamber. 2. installation of ventilation louver windows on the perimeter: an alternative system comprising adjustable louver windows on the external enclosure, allowing controlled release of humid air. 5 3. reduction of curing temperature difference between tiles current issues: a temperature difference of approximately 15°c has been identified between the upper and lower zones of the rotary curing system. this variation causes significant discrepancies in tile finish, with higher gloss on the upper tiles and darker shades on the lower ones. proposed solution: to homogenize the temperature inside the chamber, a forced air recirculation system is proposed. the strategy involves redirecting hot air from the upper zone to the lower levels of the rotary. technical implementation: the proposed solution includes the installation of two recirculation fans strategically placed in front of the existing heat exchangers. this design will: • force the descent of accumulated hot air from the upper section. • ensure constant and uniform air circulation throughout the chamber. • maintain even thermal distribution during the curing process. 6 graphical reference: the attached schematic illustrates the layout and configuration of all elements described in this proposal.", "1 COMPREHENSIVE EFFICIENCY ANALYSIS AND IMPROVEMENT STRATEGY 011025.pdf": "1 comprehensive efficiency analysis and improvement strategy as starting point of my activity as consultant, my objective is to understand in depth your current operation model to jointly identify improvement opportunities that are practical and generate rapid and sustainable impact toward the improvement of efficiency and tile quality if necessary. my initial focus would center on: 1. understanding of current structure and processes  to analyze together with your team the organizational structure, shifts, production and maintenance schedules, and workforce distribution.  the objective is to understand the current work dynamics and responsibility flows. 2. evaluation of measurement and control systems  to review existing data about efficiency, maintenance and product quality.  this will allow to establish a clear and objective baseline from which to measure progress toward established objectives. 3. diagnosis of capabilities and operational practices to explore: ○ current efficiency and maintenance management practices. ○ the plant data collection system and its usefulness. ○ the training and skill level of operators and mechanics, to enhance their practical knowledge. ○ finished product quality controls. 4. development and implementation of a comprehensive management system based on the analysis, to design and implement a practical and visual system that transforms philosophy into daily actions. this system will articulate in three fundamental pillars: 4.1. structured checklist and data collection system • daily checklists for operators: to create visual and simple verification lists, focused on equipment under their responsibility. these lists will focus on: ○ detection of easily detectable anomalies (leaks, noises, vibrations, temperatures). ○ verification of basic quality and safety points. ○ basic cleaning and organization (5s) of their work area. 2 • checklists for mechanics (preventive maintenance): to develop technical protocols for: • running inspections: complementary verification of operator reports. • scheduled preventive maintenance: ○ daily: verification of critical equipment elements. ○ weekly: checking of complete systems (push chains, demolding machines, elevators, etc.). ○ monthly: deep inspections and measurements with specific equipment (equipment elongations and wear). 4.2. staggered preventive maintenance plan to implement a clear and shared maintenance schedule, that assigns specific tasks to each frequency (daily, weekly, monthly), guaranteeing that each equipment receives necessary attention to operate with maximum reliability and avoid unexpected stops. 4.3. clarification of roles and responsibilities in the improvement flow to define in explicit and consensual manner the functions of each profile in this new system: • the operator: is the \"sensor\" and first transmitter\". their responsibility is observation, initial data collection and basic autonomous maintenance (according to their skills). also to propose possible improvements. they are the pillar of early detection of potential problems in the production line equipment. • the mechanic: is the \"diagnostician and specialist\". their role is to validate alerts, execute scheduled preventive maintenance, diagnose root causes of failures and to propose possible technical improvements in monthly meetings. • factory management: must be the \"facilitator and strategist\". their function is to guarantee resources, prioritize actions based on collected data and lead the implementation of structural improvements. implementation philosophy: this system doesn't seek to create bureaucracy, but to enhance and give structure to the knowledge that already exists in the plant. by standardizing and clarifying tasks, we empower each team member, allowing them to contribute with their specific experience and knowledge to the common objective: a more efficient, predictable and competitive factory. 5. empowerment of human capital: the operator as pillar i start from the basis that each operator is the main knower of their equipment. my proposal focuses on structuring and enhancing that knowledge, providing them with the tools and minimum necessary training so their work in data collection and basic maintenance (if possible) becomes even more effective and contributes directly to collective advancement. 3 work philosophy: my role is to be a facilitator. i will work based on your current operation, respecting your culture and experience, and we will only introduce changes where a clear improvement opportunity exists, always in consensual manner and with focus on achieving your strategic objectives in the most agile way possible.", "2 Visual, Auditory and Tactile Preventive Maintenance 230925.pdf": "visual, auditory and tactile preventive maintenance 230925 1. early detection and dynamic anomalies (running controls) why running? many failures only manifest under real load, temperature or operational speed. visual controls: allow to identify: abnormal vibrations or movements (which cannot be identified when stopped). active wear or leaks of aluminum, sand, cement, pigment, water, lubricant or fluid. irregular movement patterns (polycords, belts, rubber bands, discs, chains, shafts). auditory controls: the human ear is excellent for detecting subtle changes: pitch changes: rollers, bands, bearing shafts, pulley belts, reducers/gears, etc. knocking or metallic sounds indicating clearances or impacts. justification: a stopped equipment is \"sleeping\" equipment. these operational inspections are the first and fastest alarm system. 2. status verification and static integrity verification (stopped controls) to access, measure and verify what is impossible or dangerous with equipment running. manual/tactile controls: pulley dirt: assess pulley dirt level. clearance adjustment: axial/radial play in shafts, level of torsional displacement. tension verification of chains, belts or polycords. wear detection by touch (e.g.: surface roughness, coupling play). cleaning and close inspection of critical components. justification: these controls provide specific numerical data (e.g.: \"2mm clearances, elongations\") essential for equipment condition monitoring and planning future interventions.", "3 CHECKLIST de Banda Goma y Sinfin cemento 300925.pdf": "1. checklist belt conveyor (excel) **immediate actions:** if ❌ detected: **high priority:** stop immediately. **high priority:** schedule repair within 24h. **equipment:** tb01 **frequency:** weekly **date:** **operator/mechanic:** ___________________________ **a. visual verifications (running)** **item** **verification** **criteria** ✅ ok ❌ nok **observations* 1 belt alignment belt doesn't shift laterally (>2 cm) 2 scraper condition uniform contact, no material accumulation 3 support rollers rotate freely, no adhered material 4 material leaks no material accumulation on sides or base 5 gearmotor no oil leaks **b. sound verifications (running)** 1 support rollers no abnormal noises (squeaking, impacts) 2 gearmotor no irregular or excessive humming 3 belt no friction noises with structure **c. manual verifications (stopped)** 1 belt wear no cuts or cracks on surface 2 rollers (drive, driven) no axial clearances, smooth rotation 3 oil level (gearmotor) between min/max marks 4 bearing condition no axial/radial play 5 belt tension maximum deflection 2-3 cm when pressing 2. checklist cement screw conveyor **immediate actions:** if ❌ detected: **high priority:** stop immediately. **high priority:** schedule repair within 24h. **equipment:** screw_cem01 **frequency:** weekly **date:** **operator/mechanic:** ___________________________ **a. visual verifications (running)** **item** **verification** **criteria** ✅ ok ❌ nok observations 1 cement leaks no accumulation in joints or connections 2 gearmotor and coupling no oil leaks, no misalignments 3 greasing points visible and accessible grease fittings 4 screw structure no deformations or corrosion **b. sound verifications (running)** 1 screw friction no metallic noises (screw vs. casing) 2 gearmotor no excessive vibrations or humming 3 couplings no clicking or impact sounds **c. manual verifications (stopped)** 1 screw wear clearance <5 mm between screw and casing 2 couplings no excessive clearances 3 oil level (gearmotor) between min/max marks 4 bearing condition no axial/radial play 5 critical points lubrication complete greasing (if applicable) **"};